<HEAD>Meese's Friend Says He Rejected Leniency Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> says he refused to testify against his longtime friend, Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, in exchange for a government offer of leniency in the <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> influence peddling case. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>, 54, made the statement in an interview broadcast Tuesday night on <ORGANIZATION> KRON-TV </ORGANIZATION>, an <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> affiliate. <PERSON> KRON </PERSON> said the interview was recorded earlier and that further portions would be broadcast on a Wednesday night news program. The <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> trial lawyer called <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> `` an honorable man'' and said there `` is nothing to talk about'' with prosecutors investigating allegations that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> improperly used his influence on <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>'s behalf in a proposed Iraqi pipeline deal. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>, who has known <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> since law school, made the statement about leniency when asked if prosecutors had approached his lawyers to work out a deal. `` Yes, they did,'' <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> KRON </ORGANIZATION> he learned he was about to be indicted on Dec. 22, when <PERSON> Baruch </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, an assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, contacted <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>'s lawyer. `` -LRB- <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> -RRB- notified my then-counsel that they had to give up the arrangements they had entered into with him for a series of meetings to discuss possible allegations against me,'' <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> said. Instead, <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> added, <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> presented his lawyer with a draft of the indictment. `` -LRB- He -RRB- gave me three days in which to plead guilty and cooperate _ and then said if, in fact, I would give it some thought, perhaps they would n't indict me on a racketeering charge,'' <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> said. The station said <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> replied, `` I can not comment on that'' when asked if <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> had been offered leniency in exchange for testimony against the attorney general. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> said he was an unpaid adviser to <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION>, a Bronx-based, minority-owned defense contractor. He is under indictment on federal racketeering charges for allegedly taking payoffs from <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> officials to influence <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> and other public officials. Former <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> officials have testified they paid $ 800,000 to <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> to influence <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>. They have said <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> told them he got the attorney general to intercede on the company's behalf for a series of contracts worth $ 143 million. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> has denied any wrongdoing. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> KRON </ORGANIZATION> he expects to be acquitted of the racketeering charges and said the indictment `` appears to be very contrived and very contorted and extremely difficult to find a crime within it.''
