<HEAD>Four Win Cancer Research Prizes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four scientists will share three $ 130,000 prizes for their work into breast cancer screening, the genetics of cancer and a substance that helps cells communicate. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prizes </ORGANIZATION> will be presented Wednesday at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, the foundation said. Each prize includes $ 100,000 plus $ 30,000 to cover expenses for a scientific conference or workshop. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>, professor emeritus of health policy and management at the <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hygiene </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, will share one award with <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Strax </PERSON>, clinical professor of oncology and radiology at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>. They will be honored for conducting a massive study demonstrating that using mammography, or breast X-rays, to detect breast cancer in its early stages can save lives. <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Knudson </PERSON>, senior member of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, will be honored for proposing a theory of `` anti-cancer'' genes. Damage to these genes can lead to cancer. Evidence for such genes has been found in some rare tumors and in cancers of the breast, colon, and lung. The third prize will go to <PERSON> Yasutomi </PERSON> <PERSON> Nishizuka </PERSON>, professor and chairman of biochemistry at the <ORGANIZATION> Kobe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Univerisity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. He discovered and purified a substance called protein kinase C, which plays a key role in handling chemical messages that come to a cell. He also showed that environmental chemicals can act directly on that substance to promote cancer.
