<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's largest Presbyterian body Monday called on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to end its 20-year occupation of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, where the church said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> had used `` repressive'' measures to quell Palestinian violence. The 200th <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Presbyterian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> declined to include in its resolution language calling on Palestinians to recognize <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist as a nation. The Rev. <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Weir </PERSON>, a Presbyterian leader and former hostage in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, told the 630 commissioners the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> has made such statements several times. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> maintains that such <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> statements have been ambiguous or unauthoritative. The statement adopted Monday on a 494-67 vote said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> had responded to uprisings in the occupied territories with `` rigid censorship, mass arrests, torture of prisoners, administrative detention and deportation.'' The resolutions adopted also call upon the `` Palestinian people and leadership to exert sustained efforts to control acts of violence in order to facilitate the peace process.'' Earlier Monday, a major Presbyterian statement on nuclear war was revised to make the document more closely follow the original intention, according to the two former seminary professors who led the writing effort. The Committee on Peacemaking and International Relations of the <ORGANIZATION> Presbyterian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> -LRB- </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- continued review Monday evening of `` Christian Obedience in a Nuclear Age,'' making minor changes in the recommendations of a subcommittee that extensively reviewed the paper. The major change by the Peacemaking committee was made at the suggestion of the Rev. <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Come </PERSON>, former president of the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seminary </ORGANIZATION> and a co-chairman of the task force that wrote the paper last year. Originally, the paper said nuclear war and the theory of nuclear deterrence were both immoral, but the subcommittee revised that to say `` nuclear deterrence has been in danger of becoming an end in itself rather than an interim measure of self-defense. Such a policy as an end in itself is not morally defensible.'' Come and the Rev. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Winn </PERSON>, the task force's co-chairman and former president of the <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, Theological Seminary, complained the phrase `` as an end in itself'' was ambiguous. At Come's suggestion, the language was clarified to say nuclear deterrence `` is being regarded as an adequate and permanent means to national security,'' and that is `` not morally defensible.'' The committee has yet to deal with the major question of the subcommittee's recommendation that the Christian obedience paper be adopted as church policy. The subcommittee, which met for parts of four days, amended the paper to make it clear Presbyterians considered obedience to government the normal course. <PERSON> Winn </PERSON> said he disliked many changes, but added, `` in many respects, they clarified the paper and deleted some statements that were not carefully worded.'' Supporters of the original paper expect many of the revisions _ including elimination of a recommendation that the church aid tax resisters _ would be restored in some form in the full committee. Opponents of the paper want it to be sent back to the churches for further study. An effort to get the subcommittee to recommend that delay was defeated 9-5 and the subcommittee eventually agreed to recommend the revised report as a church policy by a 15-1 vote. The report is not expected to come before the 630 delegates until Tuesday. The nine-day meeting adjourns at noon Wednesday. The resolution on the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> also: _ Asks <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to `` cease the systematic violation of human rights of Palestinians ... end the policies and-or practices of beatings and of food and fuel embargoes in the attempt to subjugate and break the will of the Palestinian population. ... end the settlements policy and the acquisition of land within the occupied territories, since -LRB- they -RRB- provoke the Arab peoples and reduce the opportunity for a peaceful resolution.'' _ Asks the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to `` discourage retaliation as a counter-terror strategy in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and to address the injustices which are among the root causes of terrorism ... insist that weapons supplied by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s defense not be used against civilian populations in the occupied territories or in aggressive attacks or disproportionate retaliation upon other countries, and that further military and security assistance to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> be contingent upon the honoring of these principles. _ Ask all parties to participate in a United Nations-sponsored international peace conference The agenda included discussion of several decisions, including the recommendation that the pension board headquarters remain in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. A minority report suggests the board be moved to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. The headquarters of the 3 million-member denomination was moved to <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, last year. Anti-abortion groups also have objected to the pension board's paying for abortions The denomination has adopted a generally pro-choice position, condemning abortion as a method of birth control, but saying it remains a decision by a woman, her physician and her conscience. Anti-abortionists say the pension board should not pay for abortions. Another committee has recommended the denomination undertake a new study on the issue of abortion.
