<HEAD>Authorities Give Travelers Condoms and Sex Dictionary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-AIDS Meeting, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As part of the campaign against the spread of AIDS, travelers are being given the opportunity to learn how to suggest the use of a condom in seven languages. `` Sex has become more dangerous. ... This does not mean that one should be afraid of sex, but observant and careful of oneself and others,'' says a pamphlet included in a package for sale at travel agencies and train stations around <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>. The package includes a packet of condoms and a dictionary of sex-related phrases, according to the Social Affairs ministry. Among the phrases are, `` I want us to use a condom,'' and `` I think I might have a venereal disease.'' `` Only the condom can provide any good protection against sexually transmitted diseases,'' the pamphlet says. Health authorities this year sent 4 million pamphlets to homes to explain in graphic detail how AIDS is transmitted and distributed camouflage condoms to military conscripts.
