<HEAD>War on Cocaine Moves into USDA Greenhouse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> greenhouse has become the site of a million-dollar battle to find some way to stamp out the coca plants grown illicitly in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and processed into cocaine, <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> officials confirm. The greenhouse near <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> is one of two <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> research sites where 400 to 600 coca plants are being produced under the project, Dr. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Knipling </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. The other is an outdoor site at an undisclosed location in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> where the largely tropical plants will not be hit with frost, he said. He said the plants used in the experiment are incinerated afterward and that cocaine is never produced from them. The objective is to test herbicides to determine which ones are effective in killing the hardy coca plants. Researchers earlier had grown opium poppies in <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and marijuana in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as part of <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s research into ways to stem narcotics. But the priority changed two years ago because of growing use by Americans of both cocaine and crack, a cocaine derivative, <PERSON> Knipling </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s coca production was disclosed Sunday in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Knipling </PERSON> estimated the cost of the program at `` about $ 1 million a year.'' He said some funds come from the research service's regular budget and the rest from the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> Guards, alarms and wire fences are being used to keep out intruders at the installations, <PERSON> Knipling </PERSON> said. He refused to disclose the precise whereabouts of either of the growing sites. Coca seeds were brought to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Knipling </PERSON> said. He said a number of herbicides have been tested for use against coca. The chief herbicide recommended to the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is tebutherion, a product manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> Eli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> under the trade name <PERSON> Spike </PERSON>. <PERSON> Knipling </PERSON> said it is used in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to clear brush in areas where food crops do not grow. The subject of <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s testing surfaced when the former head of the project, <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gentner </PERSON>, told reporters he had resigned in April to protest what he called the failure of the Agriculture and State departments to examine thoroughly enough the potential dangers from use of the herbicide. <PERSON> Knipling </PERSON> said <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> cocaine production is doing far more to endanger the environment than would use of tebutherion. He said there was little doubt that the coca leaves were being heavily sprayed with pesticides, which could cause harm. Moreover, he said, sulfuric acid and other chemicals being used to process the coca into cocaine undoubtedly are dumped into streams when the manufacturing process is over. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunlop </PERSON>, assistant secretary of agriculture for natural resources and the environment, said coca producers, `` in their efforts to satiate the habits of American cocaine addicts, are doing heavy and extreme environmental damage.'' `` They are slashing and burning the tropical rain forest'' to clear more ground for coca planting, he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON> emerged from a visit with <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> and reported no progress in getting the government to suspend conservation restrictions to combat drought problems. `` I hope there'll be rain in the next two weeks,'' <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON> said Monday after the session in <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>'s office. He said <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> was encouraging about an emergency feed program to help livestock producers whose hay and grazing land have been scorched by drought but refused to lift curbs imposed under the Conservation Reserve Program. That program, established in 1985, aims to take 45 million acres out of crop production by 1990 and cover them instead with trees and grasses. Farmers sign contracts to include such highly erodible lands in the reserve and in exchange obtain government payments. <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> officials recently estimated the overall cost of the reserve program to the taxpayers at $ 677 million for 1987, $ 1.864 billion for this year and $ 2.16 billion next year. <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> has the power in an emergency to suspend program rules that bar cutting hay and grazing livestock on such lands. <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON> said, however, that <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> was reluctant to do so, saying the lands involved are fragile and should remain in conservation use. Under an emergency feed program, the federal government would pay substantial costs for acquiring feed for livestock and bringing it into the state. But local officials would have to apply for it. <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>'s office said he would have no comment on the session with the Minnesotans. Earlier, <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON> met with Sen. <PERSON> Quentin </PERSON> <PERSON> Burdick </PERSON>, D-N. The governor said he would discuss the situation later with <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt. <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> Agriculture Commissioner <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said the drought could wipe out as much as half of the state's crops and that the cost to the hardest hit counties in that case would total $ 400 million `` There just is no hay in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>,'' he said. He said that opening the Conservation Reserve Program acreage would cost the taxpayers nothing while putting an emergency feed program in effect would carry a price tag.
