<HEAD>Cuba Builds Air Base in Southern Angola</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> has added a new dimension to the complex conflict in southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> by constructing a military air base in southern <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> just a few minutes flying time from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> African-controlled </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, according to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials. The construction of the base in support of increased <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> troop strength in southern <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> appears to have heightened the possibility of an eventual clash between <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> and South African forces, the officials said. In addition to <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> also has forces in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> supporting a U.S.-backed anti-communist rebel group. The presence of the Cuban troops within 10 miles of the Namibian border prompted <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to call up army reserves last week. The South Africans say the Cuban forces, interspersed with Namibian guerrillas fighting for independence, are spread across a 280-mile front. According to the officials, who asked not to be identified, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> appears to be jockeying for position as talks aimed at reaching a negotiated settlement intensify. President <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> informed a gathering of Third World foreign ministers meeting in <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION> two weeks ago of the construction of the air base. `` We now have air superiority and anti-air superiority,'' Cuban news accounts of <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s comments said. `` We have the means to confront any South African adventure,'' he said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said the air strip under construction appears capable of handling MiG-23 jet fighters. In early May, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> joined the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and a joint Angolan-Cuban delegation in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> for unprecedented peace talks. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> objective is achieving an agreement that will lead to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s withdrawal from both <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> and the withdrawal of the estimated 43,000 to 45,000 Cuban troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> said <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s willingness to negotiate was the result of the Cuban troop deployment near the Namibian border. Also part of the equation is the American-backed rebel movement in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> which has been fighting that country's Marxist government for 13 years. But the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> considers that issue to be an internal Angolan problem which should not be part of the negotiating effort. All sides said the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> talks were constructive and they agreed to meet again. There has been no agreement as yet on a site. The parties to the conflict are far apart on a timetable for reaching a settlement. <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> have set out a four-year timetable for the withdrawal of the Cuban troops while insisting on a one-year process leading to black majority rule and independence for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> as well as the withdrawal of South African occupation forces from the territory. The independence process for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> is spelled out in a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> resolution. Meanwhile, Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> pledged on Monday that, if elected, he will make `` no accommodations'' with <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. He made the statement at a ceremony formalizing an agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> Cuban-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> that will permit the immigration to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of about 1,500 Cubans living in third countries. The Foundation, an anti-Castro group, has agreed to pay the costs of resettling the Cubans in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
