<FIRST>r a PM-Pioneer10     06-14 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pioneer 10,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pioneer 10 Still Sending Back Data Five Years After Leaving Solar
System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After 16 years and more than 4 billion miles, Pioneer 10 is still speeding toward interstellar space and perhaps for the next decade should continue to provide clues to some of the puzzles of the universe, scientists said. The little spacecraft, which left the solar system five years ago, has literally and figuratively gone far beyond its original mission to study Jupiter and the asteroid belt, scientists said. The 570-pound Pioneer 10 is relaying strong evidence to suggest a mysterious Planet X or possibly two smaller planets exist beyond <LOCATION> Pluto </LOCATION>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Adminstration </ORGANIZATION>'s Jet Propulsion Laboratory said Monday. `` We have a 90 to 99 percent confidence that Uranus and <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION> are being disturbed, and one candidate for that is a single Planet X,'' he said. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> and other scientists reported on Pioneer 10 to observe the fifth anniversary of the craft's leaving the known solar system. The probe was launched in 1972 and traveled an arc-shaped, 620 million mile path from <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> before making its closest approach to <LOCATION> Jupiter </LOCATION> _ 82,000 miles _ on Dec. 3, 1973. Pioneer 10 was the first spacecraft to cross the Asteroid Belt, between <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION> and Jupiter, and fly by <PERSON> Jupiter </PERSON> and return pictures. It also was the first to chart the giant planet's intense radiation belts and measure the mass of its four planet-size moons. Data from Pioneer 10 showed that Jupiter is predominantly liquid. Its twin, Pioneer 11, was launched in 1973, encountered <ORGANIZATION> Jupiter </ORGANIZATION> a year later and reached Saturn in September 1979. Scientists said Pioneer 10 is expected to operate another seven to 10 years and may run out of energy before it reaches interstellar space. Until then, the spacecraft will keep looking for long gravity waves proposed by <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON>, and may give scientists clues to the shape of the heliosphere, the boundary of the sun's influence. `` One of the principal current objectives is the observation of cosmic rays and the flow of the solar wind at heretofore unexplored distances from the sun,'' said physicist <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION>, a principal investigator on the project. `` We now have a realistic expectation of finding the outer boundary of the heliosphere ... and of penetrating into the nearby interstellar media,'' said <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, who discovered radiation belts surrounding <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. Pioneer 10 is now sending back radio signals from a distance 45 times the distance between the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> and sun. The energy picked up by a 230-foot deep space antenna would have to be stored for over 11 billion years to accumulate enough energy to light a 7 -LCB- - watt nightlight for one millisecond, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fimmel </PERSON>, project manager at the <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ames </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> But the signals from Pioneer 10 and 11 are strong enough to send high quality data on a daily basis, <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
