<HEAD>Bill Limiting Product Liability Nears Committee Approval</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Hearing begins at 10 a.m. EDT; will be led</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumer groups are criticizing a compromise bill fashioned by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, saying the measure will make it harder for victims of unsafe products to recover damages from manufacturers. Both sides in the protracted struggle between business and consumer lobbyists agree, however, that there is virtually no chance the so-called product liability bill will pass <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in this election year. The measure will go next to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which shares jurisdiction over the issue but has balked at approving such legislation in the past. Even if it manages to reach the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> _ which many congressional observers doubt _ the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is considered a graveyard for product liability bills. The measure, eagerly sought by corporations worried about escalating liability costs, would impose a uniform federal standard of liability pre-empting a wide variety of conflicting state laws. Consumer activists complain that the new proposed federal standard would limit victims of hazardous products to six narrow grounds for suing manufacturers for damages: negligence, intentional wrongdoing, defect design, defective construction, inadequate warnings and breach of written warranty. Another major feature contested by consumer advocates is the `` state of the art'' defense available to manufacturers. This provision says that a manufacturer can escape liability for damages if it can prove it did not know _ or could not know _ of a design defect with knowledge `` reasonably available to experts,'' or if there were no feasible alternative design. A pro-consumer `` escape hatch'' sponsored by Rep. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., would require only that the plaintiff prove that the product was so unsafe compared with its usefulness that it should not have been marketed The committee also accepted <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>'s proposal easing the standard of proof that plaintiffs must meet The <PERSON> Synar </PERSON> provision also would put a burden of proof on the manufacturer to show that a design defect could not be discovered and that an alternative design was not feasible. Consumer lobbyists are unhappy, though, with <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>'s proposal to give a judge not a trial jury _ the responsibility for deciding whether a product was so unsafe it should never have been marketed. Even with <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>'s softening of the pro-business features of the original bill, consumer groups say the measure undermines the legal doctrine of `` strict liability'' used by 47 states and favored by victim advocates. That doctrine shifts the focus of a liability trial from the manufacturer's alleged misconduct to the defective product itself, relieving the courts of establishing what a manufacturer knew or should have known about its product. Consumer lobbyists argue that even though the bill makes strict liability a national standard in deciding damage suits, it is weakened by including a state-of-the-art defense against manufacturers' liability, which currently is allowed in only eight states. Not covered by the bill are tobacco, alcohol and asbestos. Those products would continue to be subject to generally more stringent state liability laws. The bill also includes a provision backed by anti-abortionists that would deny special protection to any drug or contraceptive device that induces abortions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
