<HEAD>Judge Weighs Arguments In Panda Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge is deliberating whether to shut down an exhibition of giant pandas at an <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> zoo because of complaints from a wilflife group the endangered animals are being commercially exploited. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> was urged Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> to issue a preliminary injunction shutting down the exhibition at the Toledo Zoo. Since May 24, the zoo has been exhibiting two pandas on loan from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> after receiving a permit from the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Berman </PERSON>, an attorney for the wildlife fund, argued the federal agency should not have issued the permit because it failed to find that the importation of the pandas was not primarily for commercial purposes and that it would promote survival of the species. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Kilbourne </PERSON>, an attorney for the wildlife service, said the agency determined that import of the pandas would not be detrimental to their survival and that while the exhibit would have some commercial trappings, it was not primarily for commercial purposes. <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Efros </PERSON>, an attorney for the zoo, said the separate admission fee for the panda exhibit was established only for financial accountability purposes. Ms. <PERSON> Efros </PERSON> said closing the exhibit would rob the public of a chance to view an endangered species and learn something about <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. And she said it could have a potentially harmful effect on U.S.-Chinese relations.
