<HEAD>After Three Years, Vivid Memories Remain For TWA Flight's
Passengers, Crew</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three years ago today, two young men who could have passed for well-dressed college students hijacked <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> flight 847 shortly after it took off from <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>. Their act launched a dramatic episode that lasted for 17 days. By the time it was over, 39 men had been held hostage in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> for two weeks, a young <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> diver was dead and the plane had logged more than 8,500 miles between <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>. For the 153 passengers and crew _ 104 of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> _ the ordeal is something they will never forget, though many have tried. `` It was n't a fun deal to go through,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Peel </PERSON>, 36, of <PERSON> Hutchinson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION> `` We really do n't like to talk about it because every time you do, it brings it up again.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazurowski </PERSON>, 68, of <LOCATION> Lancaster </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, said the hijacking `` is an issue we would like to forget.'' <PERSON> Mazurowski </PERSON>'s daughter, <PERSON> Melissa </PERSON>, a recent graduate of <ORGANIZATION> Barnard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, still has back trouble as a result of the 30 hours they spent on the plane, her father said. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Cocoris </PERSON>, a restaurant owner from <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, said he no longer flies on <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> carriers when he visits his family in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. `` I think we are targeted,'' he said. Memories have been evoked recently by a television film about the flight, a book by the pilot and news reports about the upcoming trial in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> of one of the hijackers. <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> is scheduled to be tried in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> July 5 on charges of air piracy and murder in the death of <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Waldorf </LOCATION>, Md. The young <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> man was beaten and shot during the hijacking. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>, a Lebanese Shiite thought to have ties to the radical group, <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, was arrested in January 1987 as he went through customs with explosives in his luggage. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> tried unsuccessfully to extradite him. Court spokesman <PERSON> Falk </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said two of <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON>'s relatives and six former hostages will take part in the prosecution. <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON>'s parents could not be reached for comment Another suspect, <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> Izz-Al-Din </PERSON>, was identified by passengers as one of the people who hijacked a <ORGANIZATION> Kuwaiti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> plane earlier this year, according to a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official who asked that he not be named. The department does not have official confirmation, he said. On May 2, <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION> aired a two-hour docudrama about the episode entitled, `` The Taking of Flight 847: The <PERSON> Uli </PERSON> <PERSON> Derickson </PERSON> <PERSON> Story </PERSON>.'' Actress <PERSON> Lindsay </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> played <PERSON> Derickson </PERSON>, the purser on the flight who had close contact with the hijackers because she translated their demands from German into English during the flight. <PERSON> Mazurowski </PERSON> said the movie was `` quite factual'' though it tended to glamorize parts of the ordeal. <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheahan </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> flight attendant who has a vivid recollection of the events, said she was disappointed with what she called distortions in the movie. For instance, she said none of the passengers talked during the flight, but the film shows <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> discussing with a friend what to do. `` The truth would have been just as compelling,'' she said. Capt. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Testrake </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, wrote a book last year about the hijacking which he dedicated to <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON>. `` He looked at hate and death squarely and fearlessly, and no cry was heard to come from him,'' <PERSON> Testrake </PERSON> wrote in `` Triumph Over Terror on Flight 847,'' published by <ORGANIZATION> Fleming </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> H. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` I can not describe how I felt when <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> was killed,'' he said. `` There was just a heavy, heavy sadness that washed over me.'' In the book, which deals heavily with <PERSON> Testrake </PERSON>'s religious faith, the retired <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> pilot said he knew little about the politics of the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> until the hijacking. `` I was awakened from this typically American isolation by the black bore of an automatic pistol in my face and by the angry eyes behind it,'' he said. `` I have discovered that our country is resented in this region ...'' <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Blattner </PERSON> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, said he had no information about any settlements offered to passengers on flight 847. One former hostage said in 1985 the company offered $ 35,000 to passengers held until the end of the 17-day crisis, and $ 15,000 to those released earlier.
