<HEAD>House OKs Measure On Middlemen's Handling Of Toxic PCBs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is moving to close a loophole in the control of PCBs, the highly toxic polychlorinated biphenyls that were banned in 1976. A bill passed by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> by voice vote Monday takes direct aim at <ORGANIZATION> PCB </ORGANIZATION> brokers, the middlemen who collect the chemicals from their use sites and arrange for their destruction. While the use and destruction of PCBs are heavily regulated, there has been no governmental control over them between the time brokers pick them up and when they deliver them to a destruction facility, such as an incinerator. Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Luken </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, said the bill that moved to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> responds to reports that some brokers have improperly handled PCBs and in some instances have gone bankrupt, leaving power companies and communities to clean up storage sites. `` Literally, anyone with a truck can now get into the <ORGANIZATION> PCB </ORGANIZATION> disposal business,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., a principal sponsor of the bill `` It's time to put an end to the sham these <ORGANIZATION> PCB </ORGANIZATION> operators have put on us. It's time to put them out of business.'' PCBs are most frequently found as an insulation fluid in heavy duty electrical equipment. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> banned their manufacture in 1976, but an estimated 750 million pounds are still in use or in storage. <PERSON> Luken </PERSON> said that as the electrical gear wears out over the next few years, the nation will be faced with the task of safely disposing of a growing amount of the chemicals. The bill would require <ORGANIZATION> PCB </ORGANIZATION> brokers to be registered, keep records and demonstrate financial responsibility.
