<HEAD>Massachusetts Budget Crunch Prompts Talk Of New Taxes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Just when the presidential campaign of <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is trying to dampen any talk about Democrats raising taxes, the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor is being forced to consider the possibility at home. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> met Monday with senior budget advisers and legislative leaders to talk about his state's budget crunch, and one participant in the meeting indicated the possibility of new taxes was discussed. Senate President <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bulger </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Keverian </PERSON> both said spending and tax issues were discussed, but no conclusions were drawn. Asked if the possibility of new taxes was talked about, <PERSON> Bulger </PERSON> said, `` Every kind of idea is being discussed.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, speaking to reporters briefly on his way out of the <ORGANIZATION> Statehouse </ORGANIZATION>, also declined to provide any specifics. `` It will evolve, it will develop. We are talking about a number of things,'' the governor said. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was asked about the growing belief by some that higher taxes are inevitable. `` I do n't know if that's true at this point. We've got lots of things we are looking at and we are making good progress. And we will have a good, solid balanced budget,'' he said. The governor also declined to say whether he has asked the legislative leaders to support any new or higher taxes. With less than three weeks remaining in the fiscal year, the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> administration is facing a projected deficit of more than $ 400 million. And budget experts in the administration and in the legislature say the next fiscal year could hold more problems. The House has passed an $ 11.8 billion spending plan for next year, and that budget is pending in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The new budget is due on July 1. The legislative leaders said Monday's discussions with the governor did not focus on any particular deadline, although they acknowledged that the problem is urgent and more meetings are planned this week. `` We're running against the clock, but I'm sure we will meet our timetables,'' <PERSON> Keverian </PERSON> said. He, too, declined to reveal details of what was discussed in the meeting. In recent weeks, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has spoken repeatedly with top lawmakers, seeking to reach a broad agreement balancing the budget for both this year and next, in time to meet the July 1 deadline. Finance Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Keefe </PERSON> said there was no consensus yet on where to cut spending or on which new taxes or fees might be needed. <PERSON> Keefe </PERSON> said he was urging <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> to sign a bill projected to raise $ 40 million by imposing a sales tax on cigarettes, which arrived on the governor's desk Monday. But he said he could not predict what <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> will do. In the course of his presidential campaign, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has leaned heavily on his reputation as a competent manager who has kept his state's budget balanced. The <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign has also resisted calls from <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> to raise taxes on the wealthy, a position <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> would like to see included in the Democratic platform. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has said tax hikes should be a last resort, and that a crackdown on tax cheats should be a first step.
