<SECOND>PM-UN-Disarmament,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shultz Avoids Soviet Disarmament Challenge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> it will have no role in superpower nuclear weapons reductions and he ignored the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s invitation to ban nuclear tests. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, addressing a special <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> session on disarmament Monday, instead stressed the momentum for arms control achieved during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. `` We have made major progress toward a treaty to cut <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet strategic nuclear arsenals -LRB- long-range missiles -RRB- by 50 percent,'' he said. `` I do not know whether we will be able to conclude such a treaty this year, but we will make our best effort. `` It is the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' top arms control priority,'' he added. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s speech underlined past accomplishments, including the newly ratified U.S.-Soviet treaty to destroy intermediate-range nuclear missiles and the verification procedures that go with it. Last week, Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> used a speech to the conference to call on the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to take on future disarmament challenges. He proposed abolishing all nuclear weapons by the year 2000, an immediate mutual ban on nuclear tests and an immediate cut of 500,000 troops each from the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> replied that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will `` concentrate on results which will eliminate the disparities -LRB- in conventional arms in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> -RRB- that threaten stability, not schemes for ` equal reductions' which will have no such effect.'' <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> claims the Soviets have an advantage in conventional arms in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. In the speech, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> also ignored the Soviet call for a mutual test ban. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> similarly failed to join a 1 -LCB- - year unilaterial Soviet moratorium on testing that began in August 1985 <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> also rejected the Soviet call for a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> arms reduction verification agency to coordinate and monitor disarmament pacts. `` Some tasks, such as work to reduce nuclear arsenals, must be strictly bilateral, in negotiation, verification, and implementation.'' `` But others,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said, `` above all, the negotiations to ban chemical weapons, and the need to control nuclear proliferation _ are global problems.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> offered no specific proposals on those problems. `` Ballistic missile proliferation is a new and urgent challenge,'' particularly in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>. His advice to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> was to exercise `` mutual restraint'' and not buy or launch such missiles. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> urged nations attending the Conference on Disarmament to `` apply themselves'' to a global ban on chemical weapons, which are easily made in fertilizer and pesticide factories, but did not suggest any solutions. The potential spread of nuclear weapons to other countries, especially in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, is a central topic in the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION>'s session on disarmament and <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> urged rivals <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> to work on the problem. Earlier in the day, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> offered to sign the Nuclear Non-proliferation Treaty if <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> does so simultaneously. Later this week, delegates to the 159-member <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> will begin drafting resolutions on chemical, nuclear, conventional and space-based weapons for this third special session on disarmament in 10 years. The session, scheduled to end June 25, has been sharply divided. Diplomatic observers said it will be difficult to draft a final document. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and Western allies have called for pragmatic steps in arms control, respect for nuclear deterrence, a limited role for the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and recognition that bilateral arms talks must supersede multilateral efforts. Western diplomats also have said that conventional disarmament is as important as nuclear disarmament, and urged poor developing nations that clamor for nuclear disarmament to cut their own armies and avoid sweeping and utopian disarmament proposals.
