<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Gov. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> has lost a mistrial bid on the eve of closing arguments in his trial on charges of concealing a $ 350,000 campaign loan. Attorneys were to give closing arguments this morning, and the jury was expected to begin deliberations in the afternoon. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> and his brother, <PERSON> Willard </PERSON>, are charged in the <ORGANIZATION> Maricopa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> trial with concealing the $ 350,000 loan in financial reports required by the state. In a motion for mistrial, defense attorney <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> contended that Judge <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> may have prejudiced the case by expressing surprise when the prosecution and defense said Friday they had no more witnesses. The defense rested its case without calling either <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> or <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> to the stand. After the prosecution said it had no rebuttal witnesses, <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> told the jurors the sudden close of testimony had taken him by surprise. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> argued Monday that the judge's statement could be interpreted by the jury as implying that the defense should have presented more testimony or put the defendants on the stand. But <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said he made the comment in the context of the trial schedule. In addition, he said he did not see how the defense could be harmed since he made the remark afterthe prosecution said it had no rebuttal witnesses. <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> also denied a defense request Monday that he interview each juror privately to find out if any had seen any publicity about the case. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> was charged with six felony counts of perjury, willful concealment and filing false documents, and faces up to 22 years in prison if convicted. <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, who was his younger brother's 1986 campaign treasurer, faced three similar counts and up to 9 -LCB- years in prison if convicted The defense has contended the $ 350,000 loan from developer <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfson </PERSON> was properly reported as part of a $ 465,000 lump sum listed as a contribution from <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, and that the failure to itemize the loan was an innocent mistake. Former top <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> aide <PERSON> Edith </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> said the loan was common knowledge among the former <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> governor's inner circle. But two other former top aides, <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mac </PERSON> <PERSON> Matheson </PERSON>, said they did not know about it. The prosecution has said that <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> badly needed the loan to keep his gubernatorial campaign afloat but wanted to keep it secret to avoid harming the candidate's theme of being `` beholden to no one.'' In addition, prosecutors said it did n't matter whether <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s closest aides knew about the loan because it was not reported to the public <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> took office in January 1987 and was removed April 4 when the state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> convicted him of two unrelated charges. He also was impeached in connection with the loan, but the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> decided not to hear that charge for fear of prejudicing his criminal trial.
