<TEXT>
 In a new effort to end the Palestinian anti-occupation uprising, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> plans to force <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> parents to post cash bonds to free children detained in clashes with <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troops. Police, meanwhile, announced that they would step up aerial patrols to spot arsonists. A tenth Arab arson suspect was seized Monday night as he fled a burning wooded area near <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, Israeli radio reported. A military source said that to curb the daily violence in the occupied <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, authorities would make parents of detained children deposit cash bonds rather than promissory notes to keep their youngsters off the streets. The death count continued to mount in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, where Palestinians have for six months been revolting against the 21-year Israeli occupation. <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers fatally shot 43-year-old <PERSON> Mahmoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> village of <LOCATION> Abwein </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Ramallah </LOCATION> on Monday when he did not heed an order to halt, said Dr. <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Obeid </PERSON>, director of the <LOCATION> Ramallah </LOCATION> hospital. The victim's family said <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> was hard of hearing and probably did not hear the order. A military spokesman said the army was checking into the death, which brought the total number of Palestinian fatalities in the uprising to 207. Two Israelis have been slain. The military source who reported the cash-bond plan said <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> parents would have to pay 5,000 shekels, about $ 3,100, to obtain the release of their children detained for the first time. The money would be confiscated as a fine if the children were detained a second time, he said. Previously, families could sign a document guaranteeing to pay the amount if the suspects were arrested again after being released. `` It has to be seen in the context of a whole series of actions we have taken to reduce violence,'' said the source, who was not idenfitied in line with army regulations. An Arab resident of <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> said new fines amounting to the equivalent of $ 9,500 against homeowners whose houses were painted with <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> slogans have virtually eliminated such graffiti. `` When people see writing on the wall they take it off and do a whitewash _ they're frightened and do n't want to put themselves in trouble,'' said the resident, who asked not to be named in fear of reprisal. Officials reported more brush and forest fires Monday night in central <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, and they blamed Palestinian arsonists. Fires in recent weeks have destroyed at least 25,000 acres of grazing areas, forests and nature reserves, according to naturalists. Police reported the arrest Monday night of a 26-year-old Arab suspected of committing arson in the Ben-Shemen park along the <ORGANIZATION> Tel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviv-Jerusalem </ORGANIZATION> highway. They said a second forest fire was set near the Orthodox Kefar Habad Hassidic settlement, three miles from <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>, and residents reported seeing two people fleeing the scene, according to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio. In earlier arrests over the weekend, police seized six Arabs for allegedly setting fires in the <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> area and three others in connection with forest fires in the northern <LOCATION> Galilee </LOCATION> region. Foreign Minster <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> told Israelis Monday not to `` get hysterical'' about the fires. He said <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> militants are `` always looking for new means and new places. We must develop counter measures ... for this very injurious assault.''
</TEXT>
