<HEAD>Government Bans Freed ANC Leader From Meeting With More Than 10 At
A Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government has banned <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Govan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mbeki </PERSON> from being in the company of more than 10 people at a time, his attorney said. <PERSON> Mbeki </PERSON>, 77, freed from a life prison term last year, is not allowed to attend rallies or meetings, his attorney, <PERSON> Priscilla </PERSON> <PERSON> Jana </PERSON>, said Monday. The congress is the main guerrilla group fighting the South African government, whose apartheid system denies the country's 26 million blacks a voice in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate schools, districts and health services. <PERSON> Mbeki </PERSON> already had been prohibited from addressing meetings, giving interviews or leaving the area near the city of <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Elizabeth </LOCATION>, where he lives. The new order limiting the number of people he can be with is a common measure used by the government to punish anti-apartheid activists. Ms. <PERSON> Jana </PERSON> said another of her clients, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> co-president <PERSON> Albertina </PERSON> <PERSON> Sisulu </PERSON>, was served with similar new orders. Mrs. <PERSON> Sisulu </PERSON>, wife of imprisoned <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> official <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Sisulu </PERSON>, was one of 18 black activists whose movements and speech had already been restricted in February. The front, a coalition of anti-apartheid groups, was banned in February from all activity along with 17 other anti-apartheid organizations. Mrs. <PERSON> Jana </PERSON> said <PERSON> Mbeki </PERSON> filed a court challenge to the first restrictions placed on him but will have to refile the appeal under the new regulations. <PERSON> Mbeki </PERSON> was freed last August after serving 23 years for a 1964 conviction on charges of sabotage.
