<HEAD>Kremlin Exonerates Purged Bolsheviks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four Bolshevik leaders who were purged, convicted and died during <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s terror of the 1930s have been exonerated in the Kremlin's latest revision of Soviet history. The <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s ruling is a signal that open debate will be allowed on reform proposals at a special <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> conference this month. The court reversed the convictions of <LOCATION> Lev </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kamenev </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Zinoviev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Radek </PERSON> and the lesser-known <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Pyatikov </PERSON>, the government newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday. The move restores `` to these tragic figures their honor and their names,'' the paper said. The ruling does not mean complete rehabilitation unless their <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> membership is restored. The decision had been expected since February, when the court reversed the death sentence of <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bukharin </PERSON>, another old Bolshevik killed in the purges. <PERSON> Kamenev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Zinoviev </PERSON> were as important as <PERSON> Bukharin </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> said the court `` did not evaluate whether they were right or wrong in the old debates. But it said clearly: They are innocent before the law, state, and people.'' The article directed extraordinarily harsh criticism at <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, who killed many former comrades during the terror he used to shape the Soviet economy and society while he ruled the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> from 1927 to 1953. Since assuming power March 15, 1985, <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has been dismantling much of the Stalinist governing structure. Monday's court decision was another step in that process. At the party conference, scheduled to start June 28, delegates will debate proposals to widen the scope of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s `` perestroika,'' a reform program that some midlevel party and government officials are resisting Clearing <PERSON> Bukharin </PERSON> was essential because he broke with <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s policy of rapid industrialization in the 1930s and advocated policies similar to those <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is pursuing <PERSON> Zinoviev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kamenev </PERSON> are not identified as closely as <PERSON> Bukharin </PERSON> with specific policies, but <PERSON> Izvestia </PERSON> made clear that exonerating them was intended to foster debate. `` We are learning democracy, mastering the rules of political discussions, also in a time of hard struggle,'' it said in a long article under the headline `` A Return to Truth.'' <PERSON> Zinoviev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kamenev </PERSON> spent years in exile with <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>, the Bolshevik leader, and returned to <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> with him in February 1917. They opposed <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>'s decision in October of that year to begin the Bolshevik Revolution, but were forgiven and named to party posts. When <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> died in 1924, <PERSON> Zinoviev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kamenev </PERSON> sided with <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> against <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON>, who was driven into exile and murdered in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> in 1940. <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON> has not been rehabilitated, but several recent articles have dealt with his role in the revolution. After <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON> was exiled, <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> turned on his former allies. <PERSON> Zinoviev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kamenev </PERSON> were convicted of treason and executed after a show trial in 1936. <PERSON> Radek </PERSON>, born in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, took part in the 1917 revolution but was accused of siding with <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON> and expelled from the party in 1927. He was rehabilitated and edited <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> in the 1930s, but was tried again in 1937 and sent to a labor camp, where he is believed to have died in about 1940. <PERSON> Pyatikov </PERSON> led the left wing of the Ukrainian <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in 1917 and later held government posts. He was sentenced along with <PERSON> Radek </PERSON> and executed. `` Our predecessors, the people of the 20s, could not control the situation ... and were burned up in the flames of repression,'' <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION>'s legal correspondent, <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Feofanov </PERSON>, wrote in a detailed account of the purges. `` They preached intolerance toward the opinions of their opponents and gave birth to physical and moral terror,'' he wrote. `` In a word, discussion has been cut off for a long time about the paths toward the building of socialism. It has been restored now, more than a half century later, and from the same place; about the paths of developing revolution, about the role of the party and about the place of ` the Vozhd.''' <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> was known as the `` Vozhd'' _ supreme leader.
