<HEAD>Leaders Seek Way to Form Workable Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government of Socialist President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> and all of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> wrestled with a political identity crisis after legislative elections raised more questions than they answered. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> called the elections hoping for a Socialist majority in the 577-seat <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. Polls initially predicted he would succeed. But he did n't, although the opposing center-right alliance lost the majority it won in 1986. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> was bereft of a governing majority for the first time in 30 years. `` The country is exhausted from having voted too much,'' the influential <ORGANIZATION> Le </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monde </ORGANIZATION> newspaper declared Monday. `` It has had enough of politicians' games. It is up to the president, everybody says it and everybody is right, to act.'' Yet the president likely will find action difficult. Sunday's election was a defeat for <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, who won his second seven-year term as president May 8 with 54 percent of the vote. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> has in recent times largely abandoned Socialist principles and talked of an opening to the center. On Sunday, many French voters balked at his party's candidates. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> was making no announcements about his strategy after Sunday's elections. But it was clear he could end up with a bruised political ego in courting balky centrists or Communists. `` There is only one conclusion to draw from these failures,'' said <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Monde </PERSON>: `` All arrogance henceforth is forbidden to those who govern us or hope to do so. Nobody can pretend to incarnate the will of the people.'' The Socialists tried to act like victors. <PERSON> Lionel </PERSON> <PERSON> Jospin </PERSON>, the Socialist education minister, said: `` One thing is sure: the right can not govern.'' All the rightist votes together would not make a majority, which <PERSON> Jospin </PERSON> said `` can only be built around the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>,'' the largest single group in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. But Socialists will need help from either the reluctant far left or center. The most logical approach for <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> and his premier, <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON>, would be a coalition with the Communists, whose 27 seats would make a total of 304 for the left. Second on the list of possibilities is an attempt to entice at least 13 centrist deputies from the rightist camp. Or <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> could attempt a minority government at least until autumn, trying to find a majority for each issue. Socialist and <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> leaders have made deals and alliances in the past, but this time <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Georges </PERSON> <PERSON> Marchais </PERSON> is saying no. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> can not make deals with the center-right and the Communists at the same time, <PERSON> Marchais </PERSON> has declared, and his party will judge the government on an issue-by-issue basis. <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaudin </PERSON>, leader of the Union for French Democracy in the outgoing assembly, said of the second possibility: `` If they persist today in wanting to detach a few centrist personalities in order to turn them into Socialists, I trust my elected centrist friends to reject this proposition, which would be unworthy of them.'' Other centrists are more open to the idea of helping the Socialists. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stasi </PERSON>, another centrist, said: `` If a very large union is going to be constituted, which seems desirable to me, the center must be the pivot.'' Except for two seats from <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Polynesia </LOCATION> to be decided June 26, final results gave the Socialists 276 seats and Communists 27. The center-right <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> had 129, the conservative Rally for the Republic 126 and minor rightists 16 for a total of 271. A majority requires 289. The Communist Party dropped eight seats. The far-right <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> got one seat instead of the previous 35, and it did not go to party leader <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>.
