<HEAD>Contractor Mailing Concrete Blocks 700 Miles Via Postal Loophole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION> building-materials supplier is taking advantage of a loophole in postal regulations to mail 6,000 concrete blocks to a remote village 700 miles away. The shipments across <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> could end up costing the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Postal Service $ 500,000, and even the air carrier that stands to profit thinks the mail system is being abused. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Krogstad </PERSON> of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> Consolidators, which specializes in sending construction materials via the mail, says the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s losses are partly self-inflicted because the postal system pays 10 times as much to send the building materials by air freight as it charges <PERSON> Krogstad </PERSON> to mail them Each individually addressed concrete block costs <PERSON> Krogstad </PERSON> $ 4.33 in postage. The same block costs the post office $ 50.94 to deliver to <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Arctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Eskimo </LOCATION> community about 90 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Barrow </LOCATION>. That's a subsidy of $ 46.61 per block. <PERSON> Krogstad </PERSON> also is mailing 4,600 bags of cement to <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON>. The blocks each weigh 67 pounds and the bags of cement about 65 pounds, so they fall just under the parcel-post limit of 70 pounds to qualify as mail. His postage costs will total about $ 45,000. The blocks and bags could have been shipped via air freight from <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION> for a little more than $ 210,000, but the way mail is handled in rural <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> more than doubles the cost. First, the Postal Service trucks the blocks to <LOCATION> Fairbanks </LOCATION>, about 360 miles. They are then flown to <LOCATION> Barrow </LOCATION> on large cargo planes, transferred to small planes and flown to <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON> in loads of 18 to 35 blocks. The practice is called `` bypass'' mail because the shipment moves directly from sender to airline to addressee, bypassing post offices. `` This was not the intent of the bypass program,'' says <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorgan </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> transportation supervisor. `` The original intent of bypass mail was to clear the postal floor of large shipments of groceries and staples required for day-to-day living.'' But <PERSON> Krogstad </PERSON> says the system means his shipments cost the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> 76 cents a pound from Fairbanks to <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON> instead of the 30 cents a pound that a charter flight from <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION> to <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON> would cost. `` It's ridiculous,'' <PERSON> Krogstad </PERSON> said. `` It's un-American, it's got to be unconstitutional, that a branch of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government ca n't go out and competitively bid to get the best price on hauling the mail. Even one of the prime beneficiaries of the block-lift has misgivings. `` We're philosophically opposed to it,'' says <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Brugman </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cargo </ORGANIZATION>, which is hauling many of the blocks and cement bags. `` It's not what the mail is for.'' <PERSON> Dorgan </PERSON> says he's worried the block-lift may put an end to bypass mail once word gets around. `` The people in the <PERSON> bush </PERSON> are the ones who are going to suffer,'' he said. Another problem, says <PERSON> Dorgan </PERSON>, is that the block-lift may cause a backup of ordinary mail, such as groceries, bound for villages served from <LOCATION> Barrow </LOCATION>. The idea of mailing the materials `` was an angle that got us the job,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilman </PERSON>, owner of <ORGANIZATION> Gilco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Construction </ORGANIZATION>, a contractor building a small-boat harbor at <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON> with the blocks. He says he feels bad, but `` it is just an angle and that's the nature of the business we're in.''
</TEXT>
