<HEAD>Judge Finds Poetic Justice In Civil Damage Award Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Alas!' T is poetic justice, wrote the jurist, perhaps disturbing your legal purists In a ruling that started with a poem, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> upheld a bankruptcy judge's decision that <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowland </PERSON>'s filing for bankruptcy was no protection from an $ 8,500 award won against him by <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> Coughlin </PERSON>. <PERSON> Coughlin </PERSON>, 27, won the award in his lawsuit against <PERSON> Rowland </PERSON>, who punched out his front teeth during a teen-age fracas in <LOCATION> Bergenfield </LOCATION> in 1979, according to <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON>'s opinion. In his ruling Monday, <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> wrote: `` On this appeal the facts are undisputed; Mr. <PERSON> Rowland </PERSON>'s punch caused Mr. <PERSON> Coughlin </PERSON>'s teeth to be uprooted,'' `` <PERSON> Coughlin </PERSON> sued in the state court and won. `` Rowland filed in bankruptcy to get the debt undone. `` The bankruptcy court found the assault to be a willful and malicious blow, `` And the request to discharge the debt was answered ` no.' `` The bankruptcy court correctly decided that the debtor intended harm, `` By propelling his fist into plaintiff's mouth with his arm. `` This court agrees that bankruptcy law should not be enlarged, `` So as to permit a judgment for assault and battery to be discharged. `` To do so would require existing precedent to be spurned. `` For these reasons the decision of the bankruptcy court will be affirmed.''
