<HEAD>U.S. Appeals Court Says Illegal Alien Entitled To Sue For Back Pay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court decision that an illegal alien can sue his employer for nearly $ 50,000 in unpaid wages `` blazes a trail'' for other rulings favoring immigrant workers, a union official says. The Atlanta-based 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled that <PERSON> Rajni </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patel </PERSON>, an illegal alien from <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, is entitled to sue for unpaid back wages incurred during a three-year period. The decision reverses a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling last year throwing out the case, which hinged on the court's interpretation of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Fair Labor Standards Act. The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ladies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Garment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> supplied <PERSON> Patel </PERSON> with legal help and filed a brief supporting him. Union spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said the ruling not only vindicates <PERSON> Patel </PERSON>'s claims, but `` blazes a trail which, we hope, will lead to similar rulings on other fronts ... favorable to immigrants.'' The appeals court cleared the way for <PERSON> Patel </PERSON> to proceed with his lawsuit against a <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, hotel, where he worked as a maintenance man and janitor from 1982 to 1985. <PERSON> Patel </PERSON> in 1986 sued the Quality Inn South of <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> and its owners, <ORGANIZATION> Sumani </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, contending that the hotel violated wage and overtime laws and owed him $ 47,132 in back pay, plus damages and attorneys' fees. In March 1987, according to the ap