<HEAD>Former Justice Minister Dies at 69.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lucien </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardin </PERSON>, who precipitated a parliamentary crisis in 1966 as justice minister in the Liberal government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON>, died at his home after a long battle with cancer. He was 69. <PERSON> Cardin </PERSON>, who died Monday, had been a judge of the <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION> since 1983. First elected to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> as <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> member from <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> in 1952, <PERSON> Cardin </PERSON> was re-elected six times before deciding not to run in the 1968 general election. After the Liberals under <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON> formed a government in 1963, <PERSON> Cardin </PERSON> was appointed associate defense minister, then public works minister, and finally justice minister. His troubles as justice minister began in 1965 when he confirmed on television that <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION> postal clerk, had been spying for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> had admitted to spying and was fired by the post office without a pension. He was n't prosecuted because he was dying of cancer. The opposition in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> contended that <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> should n't have been fired without being prosecuted <PERSON> Cardin </PERSON> defended the government's position. To save his government, <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON> had to agree to an opposition demand for an investigation into the loss of <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON>'s pension. The scandal grew when <PERSON> Cardin </PERSON>, under opposition attack for the Liberals' handling of security cases, replied on March 4, 1966, that the opposition had no business talking. <PERSON> Cardin </PERSON> then mentioned an embarrassing case involving the Conservatives. <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON> had asked the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canadian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mounted </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> in 1964 for all files on members of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> in which security was involved. As a result, he had been briefed on <PERSON> Gerda </PERSON> <PERSON> Munsinger </PERSON>, a German call-girl and suspected Soviet agent who was considered a security problem because of an affair with <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Sevigny </PERSON>. At the time, <PERSON> Sevigny </PERSON> was associate defense minister in the Conservative government of Prime Minister <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Diefenbaker </PERSON>. <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON> had discussed the <PERSON> Munsinger </PERSON> affair privately with <PERSON> Diefenbaker </PERSON>, but <PERSON> Cardin </PERSON>'s blurted reference in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> was the first public disclosure. <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON> appointed a justice of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to look into the matter, which aroused concern in the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Cardin </PERSON> resigned as justice minister in 1967. He was member of the immigration appeal board from 1970 to 1972 and served on the tax review board that eventually became the Tax Court of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. He is survived by his wife <PERSON> Marcelle </PERSON> and four children.
