<FIRST>r a PM-Vaccine-Risk     06-14 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vaccine-Risk,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vaccine Side Effects Pose Little Risk, Experts Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling on vaccine liability focused on the only common vaccine that can cause the disease it is intended to prevent, experts say. The court ruled Monday that the federal government may be forced to pay damages for polio resulting from the oral vaccine for that disease. But in general, side effects from vaccines are rare, and `` it's far better to be vaccinated than to get the disease,'' said <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Giebink </PERSON>, professor of pediatrics at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> Here are common vaccines and their side effects: _ Oral polio vaccine, which is given twice in the first year of life with boosters in the second year and just before entering school. It has no side effects other than rare cases of polio paralysis, which occurs in about one out of every 3.2 million doses of vaccine, <PERSON> Giebink </PERSON> said. The paralytic reaction is most common in people with hampered immune systems, either the vaccinated child or a family member of a vaccinated child, he said. The weakened virus used in the vaccine can pass to a family member, possibly causing trouble if that person's immune system is weakened, he said. _ Diphtheria-Tetanus-Pertussis vaccine, given at ages two months, four months, six months, 15 months and at entry to school. Pertussis is whooping cough. About one in 110,000 children who get the DTP vaccine develop a brain dysfunction that can include seizures. It is usually temporary. But about one in 310,000 vaccinated children get permanent damage that includes mental retardation or movement difficulties, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. Whether those problems are caused by the vaccine is controversial, said <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Katz </PERSON>, chairman of the pediatrics department at the <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Giebink </PERSON> said they appear to be linked to the vaccine because its more mild side effects may lead to a doctor's examination, which uncovers the serious problem that may gone unnoticed before the inoculation. The mild side effects include muscle soreness and swelling at the injection site, which occur in about half the injections, and fever, in about one-fifth of immunizations, he said. About one in 2,000 children develops a fever and convulsions, without lasting effects, he said. _ Haemophilus influenzae type b vaccine, given at age 18 months. The disease being prevented is a potentially fatal infection that can cause brain damage, pneumonia and other effects. The vaccine has no serious side effects, <PERSON> Giebink </PERSON> said. Fewer than 1 percent of recipients get a fever, and one in five have arm soreness or tenderness. _ Measles-Mumps-Rubella vaccine, given at age 15 months. No serious side effects are known, although in very rare cases a spell of fever and convulsions can follow the shot, <PERSON> Giebink </PERSON> said. Some children get a rash or slight fever lasting a few days. About one in seven have a mild swelling of lymph glands in the neck. About one in 50 teen-age or adult women experience a short-lived aching or swelling of joints, he said. _ Influenza vaccine, given mostly to people in high-risk groups, such as those with chronic lung or heart disease, and the elderly. Despite publicity about a paralysis called Guillain-Barre syndrome associated with swine flu vaccines in 1976, flu vaccines in general cause no serious side effects, <PERSON> Giebink </PERSON> and <PERSON> Katz </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
