<BYLINE>By ALEX MINASIAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Iranian gunboats attacked a Singapore-flagged oil tanker with machine guns and set it on fire today in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, shipping executives reported. It was the second time in four days that Iranians raided a tanker near <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Farsi </LOCATION> island off <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s coast. The shipping sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, identified today's target as the 87,768-ton <ORGANIZATION> Neptune </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Subaru </ORGANIZATION>. No casualties were reported. They said its Asian crew, including a Sri Lankan captain and sailors from <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, put out the fires, and the vessel sailed under its own power to the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabian </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Jubail </LOCATION> for inspection. The <ORGANIZATION> Neptune </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Subaru </ORGANIZATION> was also hit by the Iranians in the <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION>, gateway to the gulf, in March, the executives said. The tanker was empty and heading for <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> for a shipment of crude oil when the gunboats opened fire early today in a 45-minute raid. <LOCATION> Farsi </LOCATION> island is a base for <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s Revolutionary Guards, who often attack ships sailing to and from <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. They also have been blamed for mining the waterway. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has mounted a major mine-sweeping operation and sent several warships to patrol in the area. It was not immediately clear if any <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warship was nearby when the <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Subaru </LOCATION> was attacked today. The vessel was about 40 miles west of <LOCATION> Farsi </LOCATION>, near the Saudi island of Hurqus. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> had attacked several ships in that area earlier in the so-called `` tanker war,'' an offshoot of the 7 -LCB- - year-old gulf war In the exchanges, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> attacks <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s vital oil shipping lanes to try to throttle its foe's economy. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> retaliates by raiding neutral vessels, mainly those trading with <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>. The Persian state accuses these two oil powers of aiding <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s military effort Shipping sources said the skipper of the Neptune Subaru appeared to be on his first trip into the gulf. `` This captain, like others we encounter, came to the gulf with no prior knowledge whatsoever about the dangers of the tanker war or what precautions should be taken against ship attacks,'' said a shipping official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. On Saturday, the Iranians attacked the U.S.-owned, British-flagged <ORGANIZATION> Esso </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Demetia </ORGANIZATION> supertanker about 120 miles south of where the <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Subaru </LOCATION> was raided. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> frigate rushed to the scene, but its help was not needed. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> registered 11 of its tankers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last year to entitle them to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warship protection. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> recently broadened the task of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> in the gulf by allowing warships to intervene in attacks on foreign commercial ships. Before the new policy went into effect May 3, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> was allowed to offer only humanitarian assistance. But <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has struck seven vessels in the waterway since then in apparent defiance of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>.
