<HEAD>FBI Seeks Man Suspected in 30 Bank Robberies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bank robber dubbed `` the gentleman bandit'' because of his penchant for three-piece suits and his soft-spoken manner in dozens of holdups, has changed his clothes and his pattern, says the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. The robber, who's averaged one to three holdups a month since his 30-bank spree in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> began in 1986, pulled his last heist in <LOCATION> Naples </LOCATION> on March 21, <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said in asking the public for help Monday. `` It does look like his pattern has been broken, but whether he's been arrested for something else or is sick from narcotics abuse, we do n't know,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. `` That's part of the reason we want to get some publicity.'' The bandit, who is about 30 years old, could be pulling the robberies to feed a drug habit, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. Investigators base that theory on photographs taken during robberies that show the man growing thinner. The bandit also has recently stowed his three-piece suit for more casual garb, and has shaved off his beard, <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> officials said. The robber usually carries a folder or accordion-type briefcase, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. While the soft-spoken man has threatened bodily harm in notes to tellers, he rarely displays a weapon and no one has been hurt. Thousands of dollars have been taken, but <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> did not give an amount. Because of the robber's mobility and familiarity with different cities and exit routes, investigators believe he has a legitimate job, possibly as a traveling salesman, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. Investigators speculate the man does not live near the banks he robs because no one has come forward to help identify him, even though robbery photos have been publicized. `` We're hoping somebody who owns a motel or a hotel might recognize him as a steady client,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said.
