<HEAD>Presbyterians Adopt Mideast Statement, Prepare To Take Up Peace
Position</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Awad Deportation, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 18th graf, `The recommended ...,' with 1 graf to CORRECT
wording of statement.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s largest Presbyterian group urged <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to end its occupation of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, calling its response to the Palestinian uprising `` heavy-handed,'' and today was considering its policy on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> anti-nuclear dissent. The 200th General Assembly of the Presbyterian Church -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S.A. </LOCATION> -RRB- also was to select a top denominational officer in an election today taking precedence over other business facing the 630 delegates. The assembly on Monday approved 494-67 its statement calling on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to end its occupation of the territories seized during the Six-Day War of 1967. The statement from the 3 million-member Protestant denomination said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s `` heavy-handed crackdown'' during the 6-month-old Palestinian uprising `` portends what lies ahead unless a political settlement is reached.'' It asked <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to `` cease the systemic violation of human rights of Palestinians,'' such as beatings, and food and fuel embargoes. The denomination urged <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to suspend settlement programs in the occupied territories, `` since these simply provoke the Arab peoples and reduce the opportunity for a peaceful resolution of the conflicting claims of Israelis and Palestinians.'' It also: _ Called on <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> and their leaders to try to control violence to ease the peace process. _ Asked the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to `` discourage retaliation as a counter-terror strategy in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and to address the injustices which are among the root causes of terrorism.'' The statement urged the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to insist that weapons supplied for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s defense not be used against civilians in the occupied territories or in `` aggressive attacks or disproportionate retaliation upon other countries.'' _ Asked all parties to participate in a United Nations-sponsored international peace conference. Today, the assembly was to begin discussing its statement on `` Christian Obedience in a Nuclear Age.'' The statement, which stemmed from a request five years ago by local Presbyterian groups for guidance on how to respond to tax resisters, was revised in lengthy meetings at the assembly by three committees. The recommendations were edited to make it clear that while tax resistance and other acts of civil disobedience could be justified, Christians normally are expected to obey civil authorities. The statement was edited in an effort to remove any doubt that disobedience is not a normal course. A section was added saying military service could be an appropriate response to a Christian's conscience The committees reworded discussion of nuclear deterrence, but left alone the declaration that nuclear war itself is immoral. The original paper said nuclear deterrence assumes the willingness to use such weapons and is therefore immoral, although it said unilateral disarmament is not yet feasible. The final recommended statement said `` nuclear deterrence has been in danger of being regarded as an adequate and permanent means to national security rather an interim measure of self-defense. Such a policy as an end in itself is not morally defensible.'' The Presbyterians also were to elect the stated clerk, who is the officer responsible for overseeing the assembly's operation. On Saturday, a committee said it would nominate <PERSON> Harriet </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, a lay leader from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, surprising many who expected the panel to nominate two people, including the Rev. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>. Andrews, interim co-stated clerk or stated clerk since the denomination was formed in 1973 from the merger of the Presbyterian Church -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -RRB- and the Presbyterian Church -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S.A. </LOCATION> -RRB-, has said he will be nominated from the floor.
