<HEAD>Lightning Starts Fire At Uranium Enrichment Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROMANS, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lightning struck a hydrogen storage tank at a uranium enrichment plant in southeastern <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and started a fire, but firefighters put out the blaze and there was no threat to people nearby, authorities said Tuesday. The tank was hit by lightning at 9:30 p.m. Monday during a storm. It is about 500 yards from the main plant. About 30 firefighters were called to ensure that the fire did not spread to other tanks. <PERSON> Philippe </PERSON> <PERSON> Baudoin </PERSON>, director of the plant, said there was no threat to the environment or to people in the vicinity. The Franco-Belgian plant at Romans, 350 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, enriches 800 tons of uranium a year for use in pressurized-water nuclear reactors.
