<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHRISTIANSBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> residents upset about a tax increase know where to gripe, thanks to a sign posted in a county office listing the home telephone number of four tax-raising supervisors. Treasurer <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> <PERSON> Meredith </PERSON> posted the sign to ward off complaints. `` I have had an enormous number of people who come into the office, and they direct their complaints to me as if I'm the one who raises taxes,'' <PERSON> Meredith </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> says the sign is just a source of information, but the supervisors see it another way. Supervisor <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> <PERSON> Solberg </PERSON> blasted the sign as `` a misuse of a courthouse facility, while Supervisor <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Hess </PERSON> called it `` terribly unprofessional.'' Ms. <PERSON> Hess </PERSON> said she received calls from people who objected to the sign, but none from tax opponents. Earlier this year, the supervisors voted 4-3 to approve a 16.7 percent property tax increase in this southeastern <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> county. <PERSON> Meredith </PERSON>, who had opposed the increase, defended the sign. `` If they vote to raise taxes, then they ought to be man or woman enough to stand up outside the board meeting and say, ` I was responsible for it,''' <PERSON> Meredith </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BREMERTON, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It was a meeting made in heaven, but the marriage was all wet. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> met <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Baltzelle </PERSON> packing parachutes for a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> unit in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. They were married Saturday under 30 feet of water. More than 50 guests gathered around a TV monitor on <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> <PERSON> Dock </PERSON>, across Pugent Sound from <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, to watch the videotaped ceremony and listen via an underwater sound system. The couple was radiant in their blue wet suits. They wore their wedding bands on bracelets outside of their diving mittens, and exchanged them after they surfaced. When it came time to kiss, they rubbed faceplates. The bride, a plant worker, and the groom, a truck driver, planned a diving honeymoon in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>.
