<FIRST>r w AM-WelfareOverhaul     06-14 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Welfare Overhaul,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Try to Craft Bill Acceptable to Administration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Senators worked Tuesday to craft a welfare-overhaul bill acceptable to the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration but said they would move ahead with the landmark, work-oriented measure if no compromise could be reached. `` We're either going to wind it up ... or go out there -LRB- on the floor -RRB- and start battling it out,'' said Republican Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>. `` It's not very clear what will satisfy the administration, and that makes it very difficult,'' said Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Chafee </PERSON>, R-R.I. Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, author and chief sponsor of the five-year, $ 2.6 billion Family Security Act, said closed-door negotiations on his popular bill would go on all day and possibly into Wednesday. Asked if the administration appeared to want a welfare bill, he replied, `` I think they do n't want to veto a bill.'' Aides have said President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will do just that if senators do not agree to demands that include broader state flexibility to experiment with demonstration projects and a guaranteed rate of welfare recipient participation in broad new education, training and employment programs. <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>'s bill would require states to institute new work and training programs and enroll as many welfare parents as they could afford, with special emphasis on teen-age mothers and others who are or are likely to be long-term recipients. As part of its emphasis on parental responsibility, the bill also requires extensive state efforts to determine paternity and automatic wage withholding immediately upon the awarding of child support. <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>'s bill has 64 sponsors in the 100-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, and an aide said two additional senators support it. Before going to the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, it would have to be reconciled with a similar but much more expensive <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill passed last December. It is unclear whether either the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> or the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> could muster the two-thirds majority needed to override a presidential veto. <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> has been fighting mandatory participation rates on behalf of the nation's governors, who fear that with their limited resources, they would have to provide cursory services to the least needy people in order to meet the required level. Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON>, R-Ore., said senators were discussing a mandatory 10 percent or 15 percent participation rate, rising eventually to 25 percent The administration wanted to go higher than that, he said. Senators said Monday that the administration was seeking a universal, mandatory and expensive workfare program, but the issue appeared to have evaporated by Tuesday. `` That's not even under discussion,'' <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> said. `` There will not be a compulsory -LRB- work -RRB- requirement from the federal level,'' <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON> said. `` The states will have a lot of options.'' <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> also said the administration was no longer fighting a new requirement that states make welfare benefits available to two-parent families at least six months in a year. Twenty-six states already provide year-round coverage.
