<FIRST>r w AM-ProductLiability     06-14 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Product Liability,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs Product Liability Bill Opposed by Consumerists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> approved a controversial product liability bill Tuesday that consumer activists immediately denounced as a pro-business assault on the legal rights of victims of hazardous products. The bipartisan compromise, which is given virtually no chance of passing <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> this year, would establish uniform federal liability standards for lawsuits over defective consumer goods. Conflicting but generally stronger state laws would be pre-empted. Business lobbyists said a federal law would ease the growing burden of liability insurance costs and result in lower consumer prices. Consumer groups said the bill would make it harder for victims to recover damages from manufacturers of unsafe products. The bill, described by Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Florio </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, as `` complex and politically charged,'' was approved 30-12 with the unanimous support of the committee's 17 Republicans and a bare 13-member majority of its 25 Democrats. It was the first time a product liability bill had ever cleared a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee. A similar measure died on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor in late 1986 after a filibuster led by <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>, an adamant foe of such legislation. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> measure now heads for further study by an unfriendly <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which shares jurisdiction and traditionally has favored trial lawyers in their opposition to such bills. `` We are getting ready for a fight in Judiciary,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., who had won the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> panel's approval of several pro-consumer amendments during more than a month of wrangling over the Consumer lobbyists lost no time castigating the bill and its supporters. `` Since 1981, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> industry has been battering away at <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, trying to get a pre-emptive federal product liability law passed that would give manufacturers and sellers greater opportunity to place dangerous products on the market with diminished liability to the people they injure,'' said <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Claybrook </PERSON>, president of Public Citizen. `` Today a majority of the committee brought that consumer nightmare a little closer to reality,'' she said. Consumer advocate <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON> said the committee had sided with `` toxic chemical producers, dangerously defective product manufacturers and other promoters of corporate violence.'' <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Trowbridge </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION>, said the bill provides a `` fair and responsible'' overhaul of product liability laws. He said it would `` help curb the number of unwarranted lawsuits,'' stimulate the economy and reduce consumer prices. `` Everyone _ except the nation's trial lawyers _ wins under this bill,'' <PERSON> Trowbridge </PERSON> said. A major feature protested by consumer advocates is the `` state of the art'' defense made available to manufacturers under the bill. That provision says manufacturers can escape liability for damages if they can prove they did not know _ or could not know _ of a design defect with knowledge `` reasonably available to experts,'' or if there was no feasible alternative design. <PERSON> Synar </PERSON> won approval of an amendment putting the burden of proof on the manufacturer rather than the consumer. The committee also accepted a pro-consumer `` escape hatch'' sponsored by <PERSON> Synar </PERSON> that would require plaintiffs to prove only that the product was so unsafe compared with its usefulness that it should not have been marketed. Another <PERSON> Synar </PERSON> provision would ease the standard of proof that plaintiffs must meet in suing manufacturers. But consumer interests are unhappy over his proposal to give a judge rather than a trial jury the responsibility for deciding whether a product should have been barred from the market because of safety hazards. Critics say the bill's provision for a state-of-the-art defense, currently available to manufacturers in only eight states, would undermine the legal doctrine of `` strict liability'' used in 47 states and favored by consumer interests. That doctrine shifts the focus of a liability trial from the manufacturer's alleged misconduct to the defective product itself, relieving the courts of establishing what a manufacturer knew or should have known about a product's defects.
</TEXT>
