ERSON> Eldress </PERSON> <PERSON> Soule </PERSON>'s sense of humor and her courage. `` Here was a lady who stood fast for what she believed in and always did it with the most pleasant way about her,'' <PERSON> Morse </PERSON> said. The Shakers lived simply, farming and producing tools such as the clothespin and flat broom. They were pacifists and believed all people were equal. Originating in the 1770s in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Shaking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quakers </ORGANIZATION> grew under the leadership of `` Mother'' <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, who moved to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in 1774 with eight followers. Formally named the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Believers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION>'s Second Coming, they gained their nickname from emotional trembling in their religious services.
