<HEAD>Government Hurries to Ease Tax Burden on Independent Enterprises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government is moving quickly to lower taxes for cooperative ventures before a new law enters force July 1, the official Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. The new measure broadens the rights of the thousands of independent enterprises that are key to <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reform movement. The announcement was a victory for those supporting <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s efforts to reform the Soviet economy and to provide a better quality and selection of consumer goods and services Last month the Supreme Soviet, the nominal national parliament, passed a law ensuring that cooperatives, owned by their members rather than the state, can compete on an equal footing with state-run businesses. It allows cooperatives to earn hard currency, prohibits government interference in their business and bars the state from taking them over. But it would have left in place a new tax ladder set up by the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> forcing cooperatives to pay the state up to 90 percent of profits. Supreme Soviet deputies called for a change, complaining that the taxes would strangle the cooperatives. A leading reform advocate, economist <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Shmelev </PERSON>, had told a news conference rewriting the tax law might take as long as a year. But <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said government experts will have the new tax law ready in weeks. `` Significant changes are expected to be made to the decree,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. `` They say, in particular, that progressive taxes on co-ops will be reduced to 60 percent and even possibly 50 percent from the current 90.'' `` Members of the co-ops most needed by society, for example building ones, as well as cooperatives selling their products at state prices, will most likely be exempted from progressive taxation altogether.''
