<SECOND>AM-VDT Override,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Long Island County Enacts 1st Law To Regulate Terminals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAUPPAUGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first law in the nation to regulate use of computer terminals in the workplace was enacted Tuesday when the <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Legislature overrode the county executive's veto. `` It is a happy day for <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s workforce,'' said legislator <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, who introduced the bill. In six months, businesses with more than 20 visual display terminals will have to provide special treatment for workers who spend more than 26 hours a week in front of the computer screens: _ The workers must have 15-minute breaks or a new work assignment after three hours with a VDT _ The employer must pay 80 percent of the cost of annual eye exams and any eyeglasses that are needed In addition, any equipment purchased after next year must have such features as non-glare screens, adjustable desks and five-legged chairs. The bill was written in response to worker complaints of eyestrain, muscle aches and other ill effects from long-term VDT use. Subsequently, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> researchers reported that a study found that women who used VDTs for more than 20 hours a week during the first three months of preganncy suffered twice the number of miscarriages of women who rarely used terminals. But the researchers said they could not determine whether the VDTs or some other factor such as job stress caused the increased rate. County Executive <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Halpin </PERSON> vetoed the <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> measure on Friday, saying it would drive businesses away from the eastern <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> county. `` The new law will cost <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> many good high tech jobs,'' he predicted after Tuesday's vote. The 18-member Legislature discussed the bill for about an hour before voting 13-5 _ one vote more than needed _ to override <PERSON> Halpin </PERSON>'s veto. `` The county executive heard what he wanted to hear from big money, big business and fear,'' said Legislator <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Caracappa </PERSON>. `` Opposition to this bill was based on overreaction,'' charged legislator <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Blass </PERSON>. `` We've heard the doom and gloom from business in the past,'' when bottle-deposit and anti-smoking bills were enacted. <PERSON> Halpin </PERSON> said he would try `` to implement the law so it will have minimal impact on the business community.'' The County Health Department is responsible for enforcing the new law. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> LaRocca </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Long </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a business group, predicted the loss of more than 3,000 jobs in pending expansion and relocation deals. Supporters of the bill were the <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, and various women's groups
