<HEAD>Committee Defers Some Space Station Funding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> voted Tuesday to let the next president decide whether to fund construction of a space station. Under the bill approved by the committee, $ 387 million would be available for research and development between Oct. 1, when the next fiscal year begins, and April 15, when the next president would have to decide whether to continue with the space station. Another $ 65.4 million would be held in an account, and should the president decide not to proceed further, those funds would be used to shut down the program. Additionally, $ 450 million would be held through April 15. If the new president decided to continue with the program, the money would go to the space station. If he decided against the space station, $ 150 million would be transferred to <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. The remaining $ 300 million would be rescinded. Under the bill, the new president would have to let <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> know between Feb. 1 and April 15 of his intentions to continue with the space station. `` If it's -LRB- Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, it could be the end of the space station,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLay </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>. `` The guy is a northern liberal. This is set up to pit domestic spending against defense spending ... DeLay, whose Houston-area district borders <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ