<HEAD>Thousands of Latvians March in Memory of Those Deported by Soviets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Unrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of people joined a march in the <LOCATION> Latvian </LOCATION> capital of <LOCATION> Riga </LOCATION> Tuesday in memory of Latvians deported from the republic when it was occupied by Soviet forces before and after World War II, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported. The official Soviet news agency said the march was sanctioned by Soviet officials and `` many thousands'' of people participated. It reported Latvian historian <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Riekstins </PERSON> addressed a rally and quoted him as saying: `` We justifiably condemn the policy of cruelty.'' Last year a similar demonstration was allowed by Soviet authorities without interference and <LOCATION> Latvian </LOCATION> activists said 5,000 people took part. The fact that this year's march was officially sanctioned appeared linked to Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of more open reporting of the wrongs conducted under the dictatorship of <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, who died in 1953. <LOCATION> Latvian </LOCATION> activists had said Tuesday's demonstration was called `` to prevent the return of Stalinist and neo-Stalinist crimes against the people and in the further unwavering forward course of <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s restructuring,'' according to <PERSON> Ojars </PERSON> <PERSON> Kalnins </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> of Free Latvians in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> quoted <LOCATION> Riga </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Rudiks </PERSON> as saying the government of the republic had `` approved the initiative of young people to build in <LOCATION> Riga </LOCATION> a monument to victims of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s personality cult.'' Official Soviet historians say 31,000 people were deported from <LOCATION> Lativa </LOCATION> after it was occupied by the Soviet army in 1940 and in 1949. The last occupation came after <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> had been defeated and the Soviets were in the process of annexing <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> and the neighboring <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> republics of <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> had seized the republics during the war. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said many of the deportation victims were Nazi sympathizers. `` Apart from those who were deservedly punished for acts of political sabotage, collaboration with fascists, banditism and espionage, the deportees also included innocent people,'' the agency said. It had harsh words for one of the march organizers, <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> <PERSON> Cirvilis </PERSON>, calling him `` a former <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> soldier who was sent to <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> on a terrorist mission in 1945.'' Repeated attempts to reach <LOCATION> Latvian </LOCATION> activists in <LOCATION> Riga </LOCATION> by telephone were unsuccessful. There was no word on a demonstration planned Tuesday in <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>. Various reports say 36,000 Lithuanians were deported in 1941 and 200,000 in 1948. Last month, Soviet police broke up a demonstration by 5,000 Lithuanians marking the anniversary of the 1949 deportations, according to <LOCATION> Lithuanian </LOCATION> activists. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has never officially recognized the Soviet claim to the Baltic republics.
