<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> promised on Tuesday to replace the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Initiative </ORGANIZATION> with a `` Conventional Defense Initiative'' to help defend <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> against Soviet attack. The all-but-certain Democratic presidential nominee, in a major defense and foreign policy speech, also said the federal budget situation means it is time `` to make tough choices on defense.'' He denied that he was tipping his hand to the Soviets by announcing opposition to the MX and Midgetman missiles. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> declared a strong commitment to <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and outlined a step-by-step plan for reducing the risk of war in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. In a reference to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and its allies, he said that to eliminate the possibility of a surprise attack `` we have to have greater reductions from the side with the most forces, the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact.'' Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, for his part, denounced <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as `` wrong, wrong'' for opposing SDI and the MX missile. `` He's wrong twice,'' the vice president told reporters in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. On another foreign policy subject, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> appeared uncomfortable with his party's plan to label <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> a terrorist state in its platform, as his own representatives agreed at a platform drafting session Sunday in <LOCATION> Mackinac </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION> `` I tend to resist labels generally because I do n't know exactly what they mean,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Madeleine </PERSON> <PERSON> Albright </PERSON>, his foreign policy adviser, said later that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was `` very comfortable'' with the evolving platform, and `` there is absolutely no distancing himself from what was said'' at the drafting session. In his speech at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> before a pro-NATO group called the <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said, `` We've got to be very tough on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Constructive engagement's a failure. ... <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> is not only engaging in blatant racism against its own people and in terrorist acts; it's committing naked military agression against its neighbors all over southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> also said that if President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> can achieve an agreement with the Soviets on long-range missiles in the closing months of 1988, `` I strongly urge the administration to go for it and I hope they do.'' He declared his commitment to `` a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> so strong and so united that no nation will be tempted to begin a war against us.'' But he also said the <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> allies must bear a greater share of the common defense burden. `` <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> has worked for 40 years. It can work for 40 more _ if our allies do their share and if we stop trying to go it alone as we have done too often during the past seven years,'' he said. `` We all know that the defense budget is n't going to increase in real terms, unless an emergency arises, no matter who the next president is, he said. `` The time has come to make tough choices on defense.'' `` We do n't need SDI; we need <ORGANIZATION> CDI </ORGANIZATION>, the Conventional Defense Initiative begun by leaders in the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to apply advanced technology to the challenge of fighting and winning a conventional war,'' he said. The Strategic Defense Initiative is the administration's proposed space-based missile-defense system, still in the research stage. `` We do n't need MX missiles running around on railroad cars. We need an anti-tank weapon that can stop Soviet tanks.'' Asked why he would announce in advance that he opposes such mobile weapons as the MX and Midgetman missiles, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> denied that he was giving the Soviets an advantage at the bargaining table. He said modernizing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nuclear arsenal was `` an open question.'' Later Tuesday, after returning to <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> denounced <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> for allowing <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> budget cuts that he said have hampered the war on drugs. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> held a meeting with Rep. <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Studds </PERSON>, D-Mass., and leaders of a regional drug taks force aboard the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> cutter Vigilant, and he said the commander told him the ship would remain at the docks for the next several months because of the cuts `` This is our first line of defense,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` It does n't make any sense. ... We need them.'' In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, he called for persuading the Soviets `` to withdraw some of their advanced armored equipment from <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and to withdraw bridging equipment from their forward-based divisions.'' He also called for talks `` to eliminate the threat of chemical warfare not only in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, but throughout the world.'' `` But while we negotiate, we must strengthen the alliance as well, beginning with our conventional forces,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` The commanders of our armed forces have repeatedly warned us of the dangers we face. Maintenance backlogs are growing. We have serious shortfalls in airlift and sealift, in spare parts and ammunition,'' he said.
