<HEAD>House Panel Chairman Says Bill To Give Diesel Fuel Tax Relief To
Farmers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday his panel will begin writing a tax bill next week that will include relief for farmers from the tax on diesel fuel. `` I'm encouraged,'' the chairman, Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., said after separate meetings with Democrats and Republicans on his panel The bill likely would be the only tax legislation that has a chance of passing <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> this year. The main purpose of the bill would be correcting errors in the 1986 tax overhaul, but the committee could attach to the bill any of dozens of other tax provisions that have been proposed. However, the number of successful amendments is likely to be small this year because of budget agreements requiring that any provision cutting taxes be offset by another that raises revenues. Most such amendments usually are added when a tax bill goes through the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> said Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, is `` encouraged that he can hold a very well disciplined bill together on the floor of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'' _ that is, that he could protect it against serious amendment. `` That's encouraging to me,'' <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> told reporters. <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> acknowledged that any bill will include a popular provision to excuse farmers and state and local governments from a new law requiring them to pay taxes on their purchases of diesel fuel and then apply to the treasury for a rebate. The <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> already has voted to repeal the requirement. The chairman said there is considerable support on his committee for extending some tax breaks that have expired or are scheduled to end later this year. These include a tax exemption for revenue bonds that help first-time homebuyers; a credit for increased research and development, and a tax credit that encourages employers to hire the poor. Because of budget restrictions, <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> said, any extension of expiring provisions likely would be limited to one or two years. The chairman indicated there may not be enough support on the committee to toughen the tax on unrelated business income of organizations that generally are tax-exempt. Some lawmakers, striving to help small business against unfair competition, have called for taxation of such income, including that from universities' sale of computers and non-profit hospitals' newstands. Any tax bill that is debated this year is likely to face amendment by lawmakers who want to reduce the tax on capital gains, which are profits from the sale of stocks, land and other assets. This issue is complicated by the fact that advocates of a reduction _ including Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> _ contend such a move would increase tax collections by encouraging investment. Opponents deny it. Another hot issue is a `` taxpayer bill of rights,'' aimed at curbing alleged excesses of the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The Finance Committee has approved a version but <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> members have been cool to the idea.
