<HEAD>Fed Chair Says Further Dollar Devaluation Unnecessary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said Tuesday that a further decline in the dollar may hurt, rather than help, efforts to reduce the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, in a speech to <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said the devaluation of the dollar over the past three years has helped narrow the trade gap by dampening demand for more expensive foreign goods in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and stimulating sales of cheaper <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods overseas. However, <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said it is questionable whether the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has the capacity to boost production of exports any faster than the current growth rate. Thus, further declines in the dollar, by raising the price of imports, could actually cause the deficit to grow, he said. `` I find no adjustment benefit to be derived from a further fall in the dollar,'' he said in a text of his speech released in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. In three years the dollar has lost about half of its value when measured against the Japanese yen. It rose somewhat in trading Tuesday on the news that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit for April had fallen to $ 9.9 billion, its lowest level in nearly 3 -LCB- years. It was the second time in less than a week that <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> has spoken against a further drop in the dollar. He issued a similar warning June 8 after meeting in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> with other nations' central bankers. Rather than devaluing the dollar, <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, `` reducing our federal budget deficit would be the most important step we can take in the adjustment process.'' On another topic, <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said despite strained capacity in steel and certain chemicals, statistics on industrial delivery times do not indicate that inflationary bottlenecks are developing. Delivery times for production materials have moved up only moderately since late 1985 and have stabilized, at least temporarily, during the past five months, he said.
