<HEAD>Guerrillas Advance on Afghanistan's Second-Largest City</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One name for Najib is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Moslem guerrillas have punched through defenses of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s second-largest city and delayed Soviet troop withdrawal, Western diplomatic sources said Tuesday. The sources, speaking on condition their names not be used, said the guerrillas have penetrated the defenses of <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION>, a provincial capital of 20,000 people about 270 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s capital. One diplomatic source, quoting a <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION> resident, said guerrillas have been entering the city's bazaars daily to hunt communist military and government personnel. The diplomatic sources also said fighting there and the Afghan army garrison at Spin Buldak had slowed the Soviets' pullout from <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION> province and increased speculation they may reinforce the area with additional troops. Spin Buldak is 60 miles southeast <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION>, on the Pakistani border. Reports indicate the main areas of combat, in addition to <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, are at <LOCATION> Ghazni </LOCATION> to the south, <LOCATION> Khost </LOCATION> to the east and <LOCATION> Baghlan </LOCATION> city to the north near the Soviets' main withdrawal route. Pakistani sources say the guerrillas have taken the offensive this spring, capturing more than 25 towns and communist posts in the last three months. However, the diplomatic sources said <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s overall withdrawal from the country was continuing, with convoys last weekend heading north through <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> from the eastern garrisons of <LOCATION> Ghazni </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gardez </LOCATION>. They agreed with Kremlin figures that 13,000 Red Army troops have crossed the <LOCATION> Oxus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> onto home territory since the nine-month pullout began May 15 under an accord negotiated in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s Marxist president, <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, said at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> last week that 34,000 Soviets had left _ about a third of the more than 100,000 Soviets in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Tuesday, a <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> official said Soviet troops on their way out of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> will strike back at Moslem guerrillas who attack. <PERSON> Vadim </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuznetsov </PERSON>, deputy head of the ministry's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> desk, said that under the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> withdrawal accords, `` our troops were not supposed to take part in combat as they withdraw. Now they can. Obviously, they are going to defend themselves.'' <PERSON> Kuznetsov </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> there had been casualties, but that he was unable to give the extact time, place and extent of the attacks. His remarks were the most detailed explanation of a warning issued Monday by <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> that violations of the accord would bring `` resolute retaliatory steps.'' Soviet troops came to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in 1979 to bolster the communist government. The <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, which already closed its missions in <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION> and the eastern city of <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, has begun evacuating personnel from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, according to the source. That report appeared to contradict assertions this week by Indian Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSO