<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dutch riot police battled West German and Dutch demonstrators outside a courthouse in <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> on Tuesday where a suspect in the murder of two West German policemen was fighting extradition. A running street battle began during a hearing on the extradition of 25-year-old <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffmann </PERSON> to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hoffmann </PERSON>, a West German citizen, denies involvement in the Nov. 2 shootings, which occurred during a demonstration against building a new runway at <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Rhein-Main </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hoffmann </PERSON> wore a leg restraint during the hearing. Defense attorney <PERSON> Pieter </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> <PERSON> Schut </PERSON> argued that the killings were political crimes, for which Dutch law bans extradition. Public prosecutor <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonn </PERSON> conceded the two killings were `` politically influenced'' but argued they could not be regarded as political crimes. A ruling on the extradition request is set for June 28. At least eight protesters were arrested in the fighting outside, said police spokesman <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Detering </PERSON>. Police used baton charges to disperse about 100 protesters, many of them masked to avoid identification. Dozens of flak-jacketed police stood guard inside and outside the courthouse and four armed guards were detailed to <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>. Aside from those directly involved in the proceedings, only reporters were allowed inside the courtroom. About 30 <PERSON> Hoffmann </PERSON> sympathizers watched from a public gallery separated from the courtroom by bullet-proof glass. West German authorities say <PERSON> Hoffmann </PERSON> shot the West German officers with a police service pistol he stole during the protest. He also is charged with the attempted murder of two other polic