rts. Measures taken by the government have failed to right the economy, which was in disarray when the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> came to power in a 1979 revolution that deposed dictator <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON>. The Sandinistas promised broad social programs and benefits. But the war by the U.S.-backed rebels known as Contras started a little more than a year after the revolution. Today, despite a fragile, three-month cease-fire, about 60 percent of the national budget goes toward defense. The <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> put the war's pricetag at $ 3 billion. Thousands of Nicaraguans fled the fighting for the cities, leaving behind fertile lands in the northern and central war zones. Young peasants who normally would work on farms are forced to fight for either the Contras or the Sandinistas In April, the government began laying off 20,000 public employees in hopes they would turn to agriculture.
