<HEAD>Oil Prices Fall Amid Pessimism Over OPEC Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Continued failure by <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members to agree on a new pricing and production agreement has sent oil prices lower. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the July contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> benchmark crude, fell 30 cents Monday to close at $ 16.43 a barrel. Among refined products traded on the exchange, unleaded gasoline fell 0.71 cent a gallon to 48.51 cents, and home heating oil declined .50 cent to 43.75 cents a gallon. Members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, meeting in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, agreed Monday to extend their existing production accord but kept haggling over whether to prolong it for three months or six months. Analysts in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> said an extension of the accord highlighted the members' inability to overcome their differences on output levels and reach a new agreement. The agreement already has been extended once _ from last December until this month _ because the 13 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members could not reach a new pact. One <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> faction wants to cut production to push weak oil prices higher. Another _ including <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> _ wants to increase production or at least maintain it at current levels to take advantage of an expected increase in demand in the second half of the year. `` It comes down to the Saudis and their allies are not interested in doing anything to shore up the price of oil,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Beutel </PERSON>, an assistant director of the energy group at <ORGANIZATION> Elders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Oil prices fell in reaction to developments at the meeting because `` the market has been disappointed by the opportunities lost,'' <PERSON> Beutel </PERSON> said.
