<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Business, Bjt,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Ruling Gives Banks Limited Underwriting Powers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Major banks are applauding the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s ruling that banks can use subsidiaries to underwrite and deal in some securities as another step toward their industry's expansion into lucrative investment banking. Some banking companies, including <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday that they planned to take advantage of their new underwriting powers before the end of the week. Others, such as <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said they would begin operations some time this summer. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s ruling Monday upheld a lower court decision permitting banks to use subsidiaries to underwrite and deal in municipal revenue bonds, mortgage-related securities and commercial paper, a form of short-term corporate IOU. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> had granted such powers to seven of the nation's biggest banks, but restricted the activity to no more than 5 percent to 10 percent of the subsidary's gross revenue. That action was appealed by the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. In its decision, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> let stand an appeals court ruling four months ago that such activity did not violate the Depression-era Glass-Steagall Act. The law, passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in the wake of the 1929 stock market crash, was aimed primarily at protecting the financial stability of banks by restricting them from speculating in stocks and bonds. Congressional legislation is pending to repeal parts of the law. Rep. <PERSON> Fernand </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> St </PERSON> <PERSON> Germain </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>, said the court's decision would not deter the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> banking committee, which he chairs, from legislating such ground rules. `` A majority of the banking committee ... feel that it is a mistake to alllow the future structure of the financial community to be decided by the regulatory agencies and the courts,'' <ORGANIZATION> St </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Germain </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement released Monday by his office. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Pistor </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday's ruling displayed `` another hole in the anti-competitive Glass-Steagall Act and another important victory for consumers. But, before large numbers of bank customers will benefit, we need to repeal the Glass-Steagall Act and allow all banks to offer securities services.'' <ORGANIZATION> SIA </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> said his group was disappointed by the decision. `` But we are pleased the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> itself has erected a series of firewalls ... to prevent banks from taking excessive risks within the securities arena which would further weaken banks and thus endanger the nation's economy,'' he said. In other <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions Monday, the justices: _ Let stand a ruling that allows states indirectly to tax interest paid to banks and other financial institutions from investments in <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> bonds _ Ruled unanimously the government may be forced to pay damages when a vaccine it licenses causes the disease it was intended to prevent _ Barred states from banning all direct mail advertisements sent by lawyers to potential clients _ Ruled the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> was similar to a private business and must pay interest on back pay owed to a <LOCATION> Chesterfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, worker who won a lawsuit charging it with illegal discrimination _ Ruled that companies may violate antitrust law when they lobby private organizations that play a prominent role in influencing business legislation _ Struck down a federal antitrust lawsuit by actor <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Newman </PERSON> and director <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> over profits from video cassette sales and rentals
