<SECOND>PM-Business Starts,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Business Startups Fall 6.6 Percent in 7th Quarterly Drop</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Business Starts-States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A continuing decline in the number of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> business starts reflects the nation's changing economic profile and not necessarily broad economic problems, according to a business information concern. The number of new domestic businesses declined by 6.6 percent to 53,382 in the first three months of the year _ the seventh straight quarterly drop _ from 57,158 in first quarter 1987, according to <ORGANIZATION> Dun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Bradstreet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Dun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Bradstreet </ORGANIZATION> officials cited the maturing of the nation's economic expansion, now in its sixth year, and a shift from consumerism to export-driven growth as factors in the decline of business starts, a barometer of economic activity and money-making <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Dun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Bradstreet </ORGANIZATION>'s corporate economist and chief statistician, said new retailing businesses fell because of expectations that consumer demand will weaken, and startups of new service businesses fell in response to increased competition and corporate budget reductions. Retailing and service concerns account for about half of all new businesses. `` While the current surge in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports will create new business opportunities in some sectors, existing manufacturers are the primary beneficiaries,'' <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> said in a report of the latest figures. Business starts are considered important because they signal the level of entrepreneurial activity and perceived opportunities for profit in local area markets. But a persistent decline in starts does not necessarily indicate a broader economic problem, said <PERSON> Reid </PERSON> <PERSON> Gearhart </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Dun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Bradstreet </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. `` With the recovery in its sixth year, that's just having a dampening effect,'' he said. `` It's not really a negative.'' <ORGANIZATION> Dun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Bradstreet data indicated first-quarter business starts fell in seven of the nine major industry sectors. The largest decrease came in the finance-insurance-real estate category, which fell 9.8 percent. Retail business starts dropped 8.1 percent and services fell 5.7 percent. Starts also fell in the construction, manufacturing, wholesale and transportation sectors, with decreases of between 5 percent and 8 percent. Increases were in agriculture, up 11.5 percent, and mining, up 2.3 percent. `` Both mining, which includes oil and gas extraction businesses, and agriculture appear to be turning the corner after several years of severe stress,'' <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> said. Despite a drop in manufacturing-related business starts, there was evidence that export growth was encouraging some entrepreneurs, <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> said. An analysis of manufacturing starts showed significant increases among motor vehicle and equipment makers, metal producers and office equipment manufacturers. Geographically, first-quarter starts fell nationwide, with the largest decreases in the <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> states, down 15.6 percent. Other significant drops occurred in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> states, down 12.2 percent, and the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> states, down 12 percent. Starts in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> dropped only 1.1 percent, while starts in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> states were both down 3.3 percent. Starts fell 3.8 percent in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> states, 6.7 percent in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> states and 6.3 percent in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> states. <ORGANIZATION> Dun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Bradstreet </ORGANIZATION> describes itself as the world's largest marketer of business information and related services, with revenue of $ 3.4 billion in 1987.
