<HEAD>Interest Rates Mixed on Short-Term Treasury Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interest rates on short-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities were mixed in the government's latest auction, with three-month securities unchanged and the six-month rate down slightly. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sold $ 6.4 billion in three-month bills at an average discount rate of 6.44 percent on Monday, identical to last week. Another $ 6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 6.67 percent, down from 6.72 percent last week. The rate on three-month bills this week and last was the lowest since these bills sold for 6.53 percent on May 3. The rate on six-month bills was the lowest since May 16, when they averaged 6.5 percent. The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors _ 6.64 percent for three-month bills with a $ 10,000 bill selling for $ 9,837.20 and 7.0 percent for a six-month bill selling for $ 9,662.80. In a separate report, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said the average yield for one-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages dropped to 7.46 percent last week from 7.59 percent the previous week.
