<FIRST>u f PM-TradeDeficit Bjt   06-14 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trade Deficit, Bjt,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Financial Markets Brace For Bad News On Trade Deficit Today</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be topped after 8:30 a.m. EDT release of new report. A
version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government is trying to tame the wide swings in the monthly <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit, changes which in the past have sent stock prices plunging, but analysts are not sure the effortwill be a success. Financial markets were braced for more bad news today with release of the trade deficit for April. In advance of the report, many economists were predicting the deficit could widen to around $ 12.3 billion, compared to a March deficit of $ 11.9 billion. The last time the trade deficit widened, when the February figure was reported, the dollar came under intense selling pressure worldwide and the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average fell by 101 points, its fifth-worst loss ever. Analysts did n't expect such a dramatic reaction to this report, mainly because financial markets already were expecting the April deficit to be higher. However, if it came in much higher than the expected $ 12.3 billion, it had the potential to set off alarms in financial markets. For the first time in two years, the government has begun seasonally adjusting the monthly deficit figures to take into account normal seasonal changes in shipping patterns. Most government statistics are adjusted to factor out fluctuations which occur on a seasonal basis, such as the normal rise in retail sales right before Christmas. The government was forced to abandon seasonal adjustments of the trade figures in December 1985 because of lags in gathering the data. Those problems have since been corrected and seasonal adjustments are being re-introduced. By adjusting for normal seasonal swings, the government hopes to make the trade series less erratic and therefore ease the jolt financial markets sometimes receive. A string of bad monthly trade figures was blamed for adding to the pessimistic mood right before last October's stock market crash and there have been other periodic jolts, including the big drop in the stock market after the February deficit figure was released. But <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>, chief economist for the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said he did not believe the seasonal adjustments will do much to smooth out the monthly swings because of the erratic nature of trade shipments, when any single month can be affected by a number of factors. In fact, one reason analysts were looking for a wider deficit figure in April was the absence of gold shipments to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. In March, the <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> government purchased over $ 700 million in gold as a way of lowering its trade surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which has been pressuring <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> to do more to open up its country to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> goods. Even with erratic month-to-month swings, economists are optimistic that the overall trade deficit, which hit a record $ 170.3 billion, is finally headed lower. `` The trade deficit is slowly turning and that should be the story for the rest of the year,'' <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON> said. A recent survey by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economists </ORGANIZATION> showed they expect the trade defict to decline to around $ 150 billion this year and $ 125 billion in 1989.
</TEXT>
