<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> ministers reached agreement today to extend their existing oil output pact for six months but failed to take any further steps aimed at limiting production and boosting prices. Venezuelan oil minister <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Grisanti </PERSON>, disclosing the agreement to reporters at the 13-nation cartel's regular midyear meeting, said `` we think the market will have a good perception of what we have done.'' Nevertheless, the agreement confirmed widespread speculation that the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> would n't agree on significant new moves to cut the world supply of oil Prices are now substantially below <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 18-per-barrel objective. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, a sensitive barometer of prices, the July contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION> crude fell 30 cents Monday to close at $ 16.43 a barrel, partly in anticipation of the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> agreement reached today. The ministers, who began their conference on Saturday, gathered to decide whether to change the agreement among 12 of the producers that limits output to 15.06 million barrels a day. Delegation sources said the ministers had haggled over whether to extend the accord by three months or six months. The accord was to have expired June 30. High-level sources in several delegations, speaking on condition of anonymity earlier, said a majority of the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> ministers had favored the shorter extension. But the minority, favoring the longer extension, included influential <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s biggest producer. Analysts had said the prospect of yet another extension highlighted <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s inability to overcome its differences on production levels and agree on a common formula to raise prices. One <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> faction has wanted to cut production to push prices up to the target level. The Saudi-led minority has wanted to increase production or at least maintain it at current levels to take advantage of an increase in demand expected in the second half of the year and to maintain <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s market share. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> refused to sign the current accord because it wants a quota equal to that of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, with which it has been at war since 1980. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Rilwanu </PERSON> <PERSON> Lukman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>'s oil minister, said it was unlikely <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> would participate in the latest agreement. <PERSON> Lukman </PERSON> said Monday that the ministers were working hard on a compromise to bring <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> back into the fold. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has a daily production quota of 2.369 million barrels. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, which previously had a quota of 1.54 million barrels a day, is producing 2.6 million barrels daily. Success on that front would lower <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s production, which could help boost oil prices. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION>' oil minister, <PERSON> Mana </PERSON> <PERSON> Saeed </PERSON> <PERSON> Oteiba </PERSON>, left the talks on Sunday. He said he needed to consult with his government and might or might not return, although he left the rest of the <LOCATION> UAE </LOCATION> delegation behind. <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON>, however, said it was likely <PERSON> Otgiba </PERSON> would return today to sign the rollover agreement. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members are <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Gabon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>.
