<HEAD>Why Is Bud On Top?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Beer Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While most beer companies grapple with a stagnant market, <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is soaking up customers and leaving some observers scratching their heads. `` That's the $ 64 question,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON>, research director for <ORGANIZATION> M. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shanken </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> which publishes beverage industry magazines. Since the beginning of the decade, <PERSON> Anheuser </PERSON> has raised its share of the market from 28 percent to nearly 40 percent largely due to growth in Budweiser sales, which have bubbled from 35 million barrels in 1980 to 50 million last year. The answers given for the company's success range from superior marketing and management to high quality products to other factors that are less tangible. For example, Budweiser appears to succeed in getting consumers at an early age and keeping them, said <PERSON> Emanuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. If beer customers want to try a different brand, and that product happens to be unavailable, then the consumers most commonly choose a Budweiser, analysts say. `` It's become everybody's No. 2 brand,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Collopy </PERSON>, who follows the beer industry and is president of the <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> investment firm, <ORGANIZATION> Cleary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gull </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reiland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McDevitt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Collopy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberg </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> analyst who is a former <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser </ORGANIZATION> executive, said some of the brewer's successful strategies emerged after the company was bruised by its current main competitor, <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> <PERSON> Weinberg </PERSON> said <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> was first to use the marketing technique of putting the consumer at the center of an ad, with the <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> slogan: `` If you've got the time, we've got the beer.'' `` It had <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION> spinning through 1975,'' <PERSON> Weinberg </PERSON> said, and <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> was able to eat away much of <PERSON> Anheuser </PERSON>'s lead. But <PERSON> Anheuser </PERSON>, he said, responded with its own consumer-oriented slogan, `` This Bud's for you,'' which helped the company recapture its momentum. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> MacDonough </PERSON>, vice president of brand management at <LOCATION> Anheuser </LOCATION>, said advertising alone can not carry a product. `` All I can say is that the consumer is very sensitive,'' he said. `` No amount of marketing could keep a product going if you do n't have a good product.'' Analysts also note that <PERSON> Budweiser </PERSON> has been protected from the discount beer battles of <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Stroh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> by using the <PERSON> Busch </PERSON> brand as a shield. But it might be difficult to maintain Budweiser's growth as <PERSON> Anheuser </PERSON> ventures more into the low-calorie beer market, <PERSON> MacDonough </PERSON> said. After the light beer market opened up, <PERSON> Anheuser </PERSON> made a stab with Natural Light, which has not taken off like its counterpart, Lite beer at <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Anheuser </PERSON> introduced Bud Light in the early 1980s, and while the brand has not challenged <PERSON> Lite </PERSON> in terms of volume, its sales have had double-digit growth each of the past two years. <PERSON> MacDonough </PERSON> acknowledged that <PERSON> Anheuser </PERSON> officials were reluctant to enter the light beer market with the Budweiser name for fear that it would eat away Budweiser sales similar to what has happened at other companies. `` We do n't like to give people as good a head start as we gave <PERSON> Lite </PERSON>,'' he said. `` What's unusual is that we've gained that terrific growth -LRB- with Bud Light -RRB- and have still grown with Budweiser.'' One of the few areas where <PERSON> Anheuser </PERSON> has had problems is with its super-premium Michelob line, which, according to <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION>'s estimates, has lost an estimated 20 percent since the beginning of the decade But he noted Michelob sales probably were hurt by a strong dollar, which allowed imported beers to hold down their prices. Now that the dollar has weakened against other currencies, he said, <PERSON> Michelob </PERSON>'s erosion might subside. <PERSON> Anheuser </PERSON> also has had success selling its beer overseas through exporting and licensing agreements.
</TEXT>
