<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market held at sharply higher levels today after surging on a better-than-expected trade report that worked to ease inflation fears. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 31.82 points to 2,131.22, its highest level since the October market crash, by midafternoon. Trading was active. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> came to 170.23 million shares. Gainers led losers by about 3 to 1 with 1,133 up, 396 down and 405 unchanged at 2 p.m. on Wall Street. Stock prices surged at the opening on a long-awaited <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report which showed the nation's seasonally adjusted trade deficit narrowed to $ 9.89 billion in April, far below the $ 12-plus billion market watchers had been anticipating. It was the lowest trade imbalance since December 1984. The report also sparked a rally in the bond market, where the bellwether 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> issue was up more than $ 17 per $ 1,000 in face value at midday. The dollar also moved sharply higher against the major currencies. One trader said the market was `` feeding off the effect the -LRB- trade -RRB- number has on inflation.'' Analysts noted that the markets embraced the trade report because it showed a decline in exports, which eased by 2.5 percent and worked to dispel concerns that the economy is overheating. Imports declined by 6.4 percent in April. Last month, although the government's March deficit figures also were better than expected, a surge in both imports and exports replaced investors' enthusiasm with fears of inflation. `` If exports are surging, the economy is surging and inflation is surging,'' noted <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON>, first vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The Dow had been flirting with the 2,100 mark for weeks. `` But we've broken out of that much-publicized resistance level,'' one trader said. Analysts noted that a lot of cash still remains on the sidelines. `` Portfolio managers are getting ` performance anxiety' fears because they've got a lot of cash,'' one trader noted `` A lot of it is going into bonds and equities.'' Among actively traded issues, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> jumped 2 -RRB- to 119 -RRB-, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> was up 1 -RRB- at 52 -RCB-, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> was up 1 at 46 ~, and <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> was up 1 \ at <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, a component of the Dow, was off 1 | at 83 -RRB-, and <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> was off 1 \ at 46 Tobacco stocks were expected to come under pressure after a jury in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> on Monday ordered a tobacco company to pay damages for the death of a smoker. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> was up \ at 50 -RCB-. Traders were curious about who purchased a block of about 7.7 million <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> shares that traded hands early in the session. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s composite index of all its listed common stocks rose 1.85 to 154.87. At the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the market value index was up 1.05 at 309.19.
