<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices ended sharply higher Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> following a surge on Wall Street that stemmed from a better-than-expected <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade report for April. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government said the trade deficit shrank to a seasonally adjusted $ 9.89 billion from a revised gap of $ 11.7 billion in March. The April shortfall was the lowest since December 1984 and about $ 3 billion down from what many economists had predicted. Wall Street fired ahead from the opening bell, with the closely watched <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average up about 30 points to the 2,129 level as the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> session neared its close. In response, the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times-Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> 100-share index ended up 27.4 points, or 1.49 percent, at 1,866.2. Trading volume was a moderate 472.8 million shares, compared with Monday's 316.2 million. Brokers said dollar-dependent international issues were boosted by a stronger <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency. Among the few losers was Consolidated Gold Fields, which fell 10 pence to 10.48 pounds. Dealers said investors took profits and unloaded their shares as inflation worries began to evaporate.
