<FIRST>u f AM-Trade-Markets Bjt   06-14 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade-Markets, Bjt,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks and Dollar Jump, Interest Rates Drop In Response to Trade
Numbers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investors scooped up <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> securities and dollars Tuesday in response to a surprise plunge in the trade deficit that diluted inflation fears, depressed interest rates and sent the stock market to a post-crash high. `` I do n't think it's an overreaction. It's a very positive development,'' said <PERSON> Thom </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, chairman of the investment policy committee at the Philadelphia-based brokerage <ORGANIZATION> Butcher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Singer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. A government report that the April trade deficit shrank to $ 9.89 billion startled many economists and investment strategists who had expected a much larger number The shrinkage reflected a big drop in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s appetite for imports and a lesser decline in exports, key concerns of those who fear the economy is too strong and much higher inflation is inevitable. The impact was immediately felt in the foreign-exchange markets, where surging demand for dollars strengthened the currency's value relative to the Japanese yen, West German mark and British pound. In the bond market, a sensitive barometer of the economy, prices of the 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bill soared more than $ 20 per $ 1,000 in face amount. Its yield, which moves inversely to price and is an important signal of interest rate trends, tumbled to 8.81 percent, its lowest level in two months. The bond-market rally overflowed into <LOCATION> Wall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>, where stock prices advanced strongly and sent some key indices to their highest closing levels since the the October crash. Volume was heavy, an indication that more investors have been lured back to the market after a prolonged period of apathy and cynicism about stocks. `` The interesting thing I've seen today is that individual investors are calling to see what stocks we like,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Karos </PERSON>, manager of equity and over-the-counter trading at <ORGANIZATION> Piper </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jaffray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Hopwood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>. `` That's the first time I've seen that for months It's very encouraging.'' Nevertheless, some strategists were cautious about interpreting the monthly trade number, which historically has been unpredictable and subject to major revisions. They said the markets were simply overlooking other evidence of impending inflation, such as higher commodity prices and low unemployment. `` I'm somewhat concerned overall because even though statistically we do n't see the kind of inflation we saw in the late 1970s, we're possibly building a fairly good springboard for inflation,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbanel </PERSON>, a futures trader at <ORGANIZATION> Gruntal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` The market is ignoring it.'' <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Timbers </PERSON>, executive vice president and chief investment officer at <ORGANIZATION> Kemper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said the trade deficit number showed definite improvement but he also expressed skepticism about its significance. `` We will undoubtedly have a disappointing figure in the next couple of months,'' he said. `` These numbers swing all over the place.'' Even some strategists who were more positive about the trade number saw some long-term danger lurking because it signaled a possible end to an economic boom in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, a key <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trading partner that largely relies on the American market for its export-oriented economy. If that happened, the roaring Japanese stock market could tumble, setting off a powerful reverberation through other markets worldwide, especially in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` I do n't think investors are paying any attention to this, which might come back and bite them,'' said <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> of Butcher & amp; Singer. `` The Japanese market is so grossly overvalued, it could come down fast and hard.''
