<HEAD>Trade Deficit Shrinks, Markets Rally, Auto Sales Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Financial markets rallied powerfully Tuesday in response to a stunning drop in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> monthly trade deficit, oil prices rose after <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> extended a production pact, and American automakers reported lower sales for early June. The biggest economic news was the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s report that the April trade deficit shrank to $ 9.89 billion, the best showing in more than three years. Many economists had expected a wider deficit, assuming exports would not not sustain high levels and imports would surge. But exports declined only slightly and imports plunged, dampening fears that the economy is growing too rapidly and acute inflation is inevitable. The news was greeted enthusiastically in the dollar, bond and stock markets. The dollar leaped in value against most major foreign currencies, rising 1.7 percent against the British pound, 1.6 percent against the West German mark and 1.1 percent against the Japanese yen. In the bond market, a sensitive barometer of interest rates, the key 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> issue jumped more than $ 20 per $ 1,000 in face amount and its yield fell to 8.81 percent, the lowest point in two months. The bond rally spilled into stocks, where prices surged and the key <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average rose 25.07 points to 2,124.47, its highest close since the October crash. Broader market barometers also hit post-crash highs. Elsewhere, oil prices rose after the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> decided to prolong an output-restraint pact until the end of the year. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the July contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> benchmark crude oil, rose 40 cents to settle at $ 16.83 per 42-gallon barrel. In other economic news, major automakers said sales of domestically built cars and light trucks fell 4.1 percent in early June from last year's levels for the same period. But industry analysts attributed the decline largely to buying incentives last year that inflated sales. They said that 1988 spring sales have held steady and consumer confidence remains strong. Car sales were down for all domestic makers except <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which was just beginning <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production last year, and <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which began <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production in September.
