<HEAD>Government Asks Prison Term</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal prosecutors are seeking a `` substantial'' prison sentence for the former head of <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, who was convicted of distributing phony apple juice for babies, according to court papers filed Tuesday. Former Beech-Nut Chief Executive <PERSON> Neils </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON>, 54, was found guilty in February of 351 counts of violating the Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act. Each count carries a maximum sentence of three years in prison and a $ 10,000 fine. He and his co-defendant, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lavery </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION> vice president, are scheduled for sentencing Thursday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>. The government has urged <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> to impose a `` substantial'' prison sentence for <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON> because he has not shown remorse and because he allegedly gave false testimony, according to a response letter from <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Brendan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who said the arguments had no merit. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> said the government's pre-sentencing memorandum would not be made public until the day of sentencing <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> has asked that <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON> be spared a prison term and that he instead receive probation and community service or home detention. In his pre-sentencing memo, <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> suggested that <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON> could lecture to business students so they could learn from his mistakes. `` Mr. <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON> has been branded as a convicted felon and will bear the stigma of his convictions for as long as he lives,'' <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said in his letter. `` This prosecution has already ` sent a message' to the food industry that economic adulteration will not be overlooked and may result in criminal liability.'' Hoyvald and <PERSON> Lavery </PERSON> were charged in an indictment that accused Beech-Nut of shipping adulterated and misbranded juice made from phony concentrate throughout the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and overseas from 1978 to 1983. The juice, labeled 100 percent apple juice for babies, was actually made from a flavored concentrate that had little or no apple juice, prosecutors charged. There has been no evidence that the phony juice caused any health problems. Beech-Nut, the corporation, pleaded guilty in November to 215 counts of violating federal food and drug laws and agreed to pay a $ 2 million fine. <PERSON> Lavery </PERSON>, who oversaw the upstate manufacturing where the juice was made, was convicted conspiracy, 18 counts of mail fraud and 429 counts of violating federal food and drug laws. <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, is a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Nestle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S.A. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>.
