<FIRST>u f AM-ShuttleTest 1stLd-Writethru f0210 06-14 0766</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle Test, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0210,0787</SECOND>
<HEAD>Morton Thiokol, NASA Conduct Next-To-Last Shuttle Test</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to update with officials' comments on
test, picking up at the 10th graf previous, `The booster...'; Also
moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> test-fired its redesigned solid fuel booster rocket Tuesday with no apparent problems in the second-to-last test before shuttle flights are to resume. `` All indications are we had an excellent test,'' said <PERSON> Royce </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, solid rocket program manager for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. `` Everything went smoothly. The motor performed very, very well.'' Brilliant yellow flame erupted from the 126-foot-long rocket and grayish-brown smoke billowed thousands of feet into the air amid a roar that could be heard for miles. The 122-second horizontal test, conducted at 1 p.m. MDT at <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION>'s Wasatch Operations plant west of here, was the fourth of five tests required to qualify major design features of the solid fuel booster before the shuttle program, grounded after the 1986 Challenger disaster, can resume. `` We've got a lot of work to do,'' said <PERSON> J.R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Marshall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION> `` Barring some surprise, I feel very good about'' an August launch. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> vice president of engineering, said preliminary data indicated that the motor successfully withstood the simulated liftoff and flight stresses. `` From all aspects, we can say it was a totally successful test,'' <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> said. `` I hope it looks as good from the inside as it does on the outside.'' `` It's an extremely good test,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said. He said engineers will spend the next two days studying computer readouts of the test and disassembling the motor, and officials expect to have a complete analysis within two weeks. Fifteen minutes after the test, a nozzle exit cone toppled from the rear of the motor to simulate its separation from the motor during a flight. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> has scheduled an Aug. 31 launch of the shuttle Discovery. The booster tested Tuesday was free of planned flaws introduced in previous tests to determine whether the joint can withstand the intense heat and pressures of launch even in the event of some failures, <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Rocky </PERSON> <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> said. It also was the first use of a new $ 22 million test stand, which has 1,216 channels of instrumentation and uses hydraulic struts to duplicate steering, flight turbulence and other stresses the motor will endure during launch, he said. The building also can heat an entire motor to 110 degrees Fahrenheit or cool it to 20 degrees. The rocket's 1.1 million pounds of propellant has been heated to a uniform 90 degrees, or about 20 degrees warmer than the usual launch temperature, to allow engineers to test its performance at the upper limit for an actual launch, <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> said. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ewing </PERSON>, deputy director of program management for <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION>, said the hydraulic struts that duplicate launch stresses are based on `` the worst-case sideloads'' experienced in past shuttle flights. During launch the boosters flex about 26 inches at the tip, creating a `` twang,'' he said. The test simulated those pressures on the rocket motor's joints. The Challenger explosion on Jan. 28, 1986, was blamed on a faulty booster joint that allowed a plume of superhot gas to snake through an O-ring, triggering the blast that killed the seven crew members. The new joint incorporates three Viton O-rings instead of two, a metal lip to help hold the joint together and an adhesively bonded relief slot that reduces stresses and increases the sealing action of the bonded surface under pressure, <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> said. Moreover, the rocket's three field joints are equipped with heaters to maintain a minimum temperature of 75 degrees Fahrenheit. Sub-freezing temperatures the night before the doomed Challenger launch were found to have contributed to the failure of the joint. For the experiment simulating the nozzle exit cone's separation during flight, the test device was fitted with an explosive severance system activated 15 minutes after the test. Dozens of visitors from Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> and various subcontractors were at the remote desert plant to watch Tuesday's test. The final full-scale test is scheduled for some time in July. At that time, severe flaws will be introduced in the joints `` to test the system to its limits,'' <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> said. Testing of the redesigned motor has gone so well, he said, that Discovery's two boosters were hooked up Friday with an external fuel tank at <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, and the stack was to be joined with the shuttle Thursday.
</TEXT>
